<FIRST>u a AM-Iran-Toxins     08-13 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Toxins,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Iran Tried to Buy Toxins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has tried to buy poison-producing strains
of fungus from Canada and the Netherlands, according to The New
York Times.
   The disclosure that Iran was seeking the toxins renewed concerns
that the country is trying to develop a weapon from the substances,
Western intelligence officials said in Sunday editions of the Times.
   American officials said the efforts could be part of a research
program to develop a defense against biological weapons. But, an
American official, speaking about the Bush administration's
decision to urge the Canadians and Dutch to block the sale, said:
``There are enough bad vibes that we want to stand in the way of
it. We're bending over backwards to be careful.''
   The Iranians were seeking to buy types of fungus found on wheat
and grass that produce toxins called mycotoxins which can harm
humans and animals by inhibiting the ability of cells to synthesize
proteins, the newspaper said.
   The United States in 1982 asserted that mycotoxins were used in
a weapon that sprayed ``yellow rain'' on the Hmong tribespeople in
Laos by communist forces.
   Iran began trying to buy the fungus last December when a man
identified in intelligence files only as Mr. Moallem got in touch
with Dr. H. Bruno Schiefer, director of the toxicology research
center at the University of Saskatchewan.
   Schiefer thought it unusual because the purchase of such fungus
is usually from one of many laboratories around the world and not
from one scientist to another, the paper said. So Schiefer
contacted the Canadian government and he subsequently declined to
sell them the fungus.
   Soon after that, the Iranian Research Organization for Science
and Technology tried to buy 11 types of fungus from the Fungus
Cultures in the Netherlands, the paper said.
   The Dutch rejected the offer.
</TEXT>
