<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 0339EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-SriLanka     08-13 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sri Lanka,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>TV Editor Assassinated by Gunmen on Bicycle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bicycle-riding Sinhalese gunmen on
Sunday assassinated the government television's chief news editor,
the third prominent broadcast official to be killed in the past 24
days, military officials said.
   Kulasiri Amaratunga, 62, was shot in the neck Sunday morning at
his home in Mount Lavinia, a seaside resort town 6 miles south of
Colombo, according to the officials, who under briefing rules
cannot be identified.
   The assassins cut the telephone lines at Armatunga's house and
escaped on their bicycles, the officials added.
   They blamed the killing on the People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese extremist group accused of killing two other broadcast
personalities last month as part of its violent campaign against
the Sinhalese-dominated government. More than 4,000 people have
been killed in the past two years after the front condemned the
government for its peacemaking efforts with the Tamil minority.
   All three government broadcasters who were killed were Sinhalese.
   The Sri Lankan military officials reported 13 other killings in
other violence during a 24-hour period ending at 8 a.m. Sunday.
</TEXT>
