<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 0538EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Lebanon     08-13 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Lebanon,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrians Reportedly Overtake Strategic Mountain Town; Rocket Duels
In Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian troops reportedly overran a
Christian-held strategic mountaintop town Sunday, tightening the
noose around the Christian heartland as savage rocket and artillery
duels raged in Beirut.
   There was no immediate casualty report from the confrontation in
the town of Souk al-Gharb, but police said at least four people
were killed and 27 wounded in the indiscriminate exchanges across
the capital Sunday.
   A police spokesman acknowledged that the count did not include
many civilians trapped under blazing buildings in Christian east
Beirut.
   ``No one can reach them because of the intensity of the
shelling,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
standing regulations.
   The new casualties brought the overall toll to 626 killed and
1,660 wounded since March 8 when the latest confrontation erupted
between army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's 20,000 predominantly
Christian troops and Syria's 40,000 soldiers and their Moslem
militia allies.
   The siege started one week after Aoun blockaded illegal ports
run by Moslem militias south of Beirut in an effort to recoup $100
million in customs dues lost annually.
   A spokesman for Aoun said the mainly Christian units controlling
Souk al-Gharb foiled an attempt to capture the town and mounted a
counterattack, engaging Syrian, Palestinian and Druse forces in
fierce close-quarter combat.
   But an official of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive
Socialist Party said the Syrian army's 41st brigade, led by Brig.
Gen. Hashem Moallak, overran Souk al-Gharb and surrounding hilltop
hamlets Sunday.
   It was the first major ground thrust reported since the current
round of fighting erupted in March.
   The Druse official, who refused to be named, said Druse
militiamen and Palestinian dissidents opposed to Palestine
Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat, took part in the
tank-led attack on Souk al-Gharb, 15 miles southeast of Beirut.
   Police said they could not confirm or deny either of the
conflicting claims but reported heavy fighting in Souk al-Gharb.
   Since September of last year, Aoun has headed a Christian
government rivaled by a Moslem Cabinet that is led by Salim Hoss
and backed by Syria.
</TEXT>
