<FIRST>r i BC-NorthernIreland     08-13 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northern Ireland,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rioting Follows Protestant March in Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were attacked with
gasoline bombs early Sunday in rioting that followed a Protestant
parade celebrating a 300-year-old victory over the forces of a
Roman Catholic king.
   Police used batons to disperse the crowd of 200 gathered in an
area of the city where disturbances are common after the annual
Apprentice Boys' Parade.
   ``Officers were attacked by petrol bombs thrown by a riotous mob
of 200,'' said a spokesman for the Royal Ulster Constabulary, a
British police force.
   No injuries were reported, he said on condition of anonymity.
   Twenty years ago, the Apprentice Boys' Parade caused riots in
Roman Catholic districts of Londonderry and led to the dispatching
of British troops to Northern Ireland three days later on Aug. 14,
1969.
   Catholics plan their own march Monday to mark the anniversary,
followed by a speech by Bernadette Devlin McAliskey, a prominent
figure in the republican movement in the 1960s.
   On Saturday, four hours before thousands of Protestants marched
peacefully along city streets banging drums, security forces found
a bomb in a bar near a gate to the Catholic section of Londonderry,
known as Bogside.
   The bomb went off as it was being defused by British army
experts. It shattered glass in the Apprentice Boys Memorial Hall,
but no one was injured.
   The Irish Republican Army later claimed responsibility and said
in a statement that the bomb was timed to go off while security
forces toured the area to demonstrate the IRA could strike in spite
of tight security.
