<FIRST>r a BC-PhoneTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0633 08-13 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Phone Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0633,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talks Continue Past Deadline at 2 `Baby Bells'; Ameritech Union Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `We're apart...', to CORRECT spelling of Wooldridge.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone workers and regional phone companies serving 19 states
continued talks past a strike deadline Sunday, but nearly 40,000
workers in five Midwestern states walked out when negotiations
broke down there.
   Communications Workers of America members walked out at
Chicago-based Ameritech and its subsidiaries shortly after 1 a.m.
EDT (midnight CDT.)
   In Colorado, CWA and U S West representatives bargained through
the night, while in St. Louis, negotiators for the union and
Southwestern Bell broke early Sunday morning to get some rest but
planned to resume their talks later in the day. No strike was
called at those two companies.
   ``All of our people are still working, and we hope we can keep
everybody at work today while we negotiate this afternoon and get a
settlement late this afternoon or early this evening,'' said
Jennings Wooldridge, a CWA spokesman in St. Louis, referring to the
Southwestern Bell situation.
   ``We're apart on some major items that are on table,'' he said.
``There are some things we can't accept, things we need to work
out.'' Wooldridge would not specify what issues remain unresolved.
   In a telephone recording on the U S West talks, CWA local
president Mary Blue said that as of 8 a.m. EDT, ``intense
negotiations are still continuing. we are not officially on strike
at this time. everything is on hold. But it could go either way.''
   U S West spokeswoman Debbie Thomas also said the two sides are
``still talking.''
   The walkout at Ameritech brings to four the number of so-called
``Baby Bells'' affected by strikes. Ameritech and its subsidiaries
serve 12.3 million customers in Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio
and Wisconsin.
   Strikes by CWA and International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers members began a week ago at New York-based NYNEX,
Philadelphia-based Bell Atlantic, and San Francisco-based Pacific
Telesis. Together, they serve 15 states.
   No formal talks were held Saturday in those walkouts. The chief
issues in most of the talks has been wages and company efforts to
get workers to pay part of their health insurance costs.
   The walkouts have disrupted operator and repair services, but
most direct-dial calls are not affected.
   The Baby Bell companies were created in 1984 by the breakup of
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph. The only regional company to settle
so far is Atlanta-based BellSouth, which provides service in nine
states.
   Ameritech has 39,500 CWA workers on strike, and 18,000 IBEW
workers, most of whom have reached a separate settlement with one
Ameritech subsidiary, Illinois Bell.
   Southwestern Bell has 11 million customers in Missouri, Kansas,
Oklahoma, Arkansas and Texas, and has 44,000 CWA workers and no
IBEW workers.
   U S West, based in Englewood, Colo., serves 11.8 million
customers in 14 states: Arizona, Colorado, Idaho, Iowa, Minnesota,
Montana, Nebraska, New Mexico, North Dakota, Oregon, South Dakota,
Utah, Washington and Wyoming. It has 42,000 CWA workers and 2,000
IBEW workers.
