<FIRST>u i BC-Ethiopia-Leland 5thLd-Writethru a0637 08-13 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ethiopia-Leland, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0637,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wreckage of Leland's Plane Found, No Survivors Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 7th pvs, ``Leland, a...'' to UPDATE with
comment from President Bush. Pickup 8th pvs, ``The twin-engine...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers on Sunday located
the wreckage of a plane that crashed six days ago with Rep. Mickey
Leland and 15 other people aboard. U.S. officials said no survivors
were found.
   The plane crashed in Gambela, a town in southwestern Ethiopia 30
miles from the Sudanese border and 60 miles from the refugee camp
where the aircraft was headed, said James Haley, a spokesman for
the U.S. Embassy in Addis Ababa.
   The plane went down in rugged highlands near two dirt airstrips
the pilot may have been trying to reach because of bad weather near
the refugee camp.
   ``The crash site was located. U.S. helicopters put down. They
have confirmed 13 dead, and the presumption is that the other three
are also dead,'' Haley said in a telephone interivew.
   In Washington, the Pentagon issued a statement saying U.S.
helicopters discovered the crash site, ``Air Force jumpers jumped
out of a UH-60 helicopter and ... they confirmed there were no
survivors at the site.''
   However, spokesman Mel Sudin, who read the statement, also said
the jumpers accounted for only 13 people and that it appeared that
three were missing.
   Leland, a Texas Democrat who heads the House Select Committee on
Hunger, was accompanied by eight Americans. They included three
members of his staff, a friend of the congressman, three workers
for the U.S. Agency for International Development, and the wife of
one of the AID officials.
   President Bush said in Washington, ``Barbara and I were truly
saddened to hear that the discovery of Mickey Leland's aircraft
revealed that apparently there were no survivors of this tragic
accident. Mickey Leland and the other members of his traveling
party, both Americans and Ethiopians, were engaged in a noble cause
_ trying to feed the hungry.
   ``I have known, admired and worked with Mickey Leland for many
years. His sense of compassion and desire to help those in need has
aided millions of people from Houston to Addis Ababa.''
   The twin-engine Twin Otter vanished Aug. 7 in bad weather. The
rescue workers did not immediately speculate on the cause of the
crash.
   However, Gambela and the village of Dembidola just to the north
had been an early focus of the search because there are two rough,
dirt airstrips nearby.
   The pilot may have diverted to one of those strips because of
heavy clouds and low visibility at Leland's intended destination.
   The Ethiopian government said peasants had heard a light plane
circling one and possibly two other dirt strips 90 miles southeast
of Gambela on Monday.
   Since the plane disappeared, an aerial and ground search by U.S.
and Ethiopian personnel had been carried out daily. At one point,
weather satellites detected what appeared to be airplane distress
signals far from the intended flight path, but a search of those
areas turned up nothing.
   The seven others on board were all Ethiopian. They included a
three-member crew, an officer with the Foreign Ministry, an officer
of Ethiopia's Research and Rehabilitation Commission, another
official and an employee of AID.
   Earlier Sunday, U.S. and Ethiopian rescuers had extended their
search for Leland's Twin Otter airplane into eastern Sudan. On
Saturday, searchers had concentrated their efforts on valleys and
mountains in a 100,000-square-mile area about the size of Wyoming.
   Another Embassy spokesman, John Guerra, said four U.S. Army
Blackhawk helicopters and six other aircraft searched Sunday along
the path the plane was to take to the camp in Fugnido, 480 miles
southwest of Addis Ababa.
   Ethiopian authorities said it was cloudy in the search area and
visibility was poor Sunday. Bad weather had dogged the operation
since it began Tuesday.
   Fugnido is the site of one of four refugee camps in southwestern
Ethiopia run by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. Fugnido
houses more than 300,000 Sudanese who have fled famine and a civil
war in their own country.
   A C-141 Hercules aircraft with additional personnel and
equipment arrived Saturday to help in the search.
   The reinforcements, including 100 more searchers, were sent
mainly to relieve fliers of two Hercules already involved in the
effort. They had been flying from dawn to sunset since they arrived
from West Germany on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
