<FIRST>u a BC-SpaceShuttle 4thLd-Writethru a0636 08-13 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Space Shuttle, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0636,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Lands Safely In California After Secret Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4-7th grafs, bgng `Earlier, sonic...', with 5 grafs to
UPDATE with inspection, a few tiles missing, and to recast. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, `The weather...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Columbia
swooped out of orbit and landed safely in the Mojave Desert on
Sunday at the end of a secret mission in which the astronauts
released a superspy satellite to photograph military targets around
the globe.
   Air Force Col. Brewster Shaw, commander of the five-man crew,
guided the 97-ton winged spaceship to a touchdown on a hard clay
runway at 6:37 a.m. PDT after a flight that covered more than 2
million miles in five days, one hour.
   ``A super team and a great machine _ welcome home, Columbia,''
Frank Culbertson, an astronaut who served as the spacecraft
communicator at Mission Control in Houston, told the crew as the
spacecraft rolled down the runway after a perfect landing.
   After securing systems aboard the spacecraft for nearly an hour,
the astronauts left the vehicle and did a walkaround inspection.
They found a few of the 30,000 heat protection tiles missing, a
normal condition.
   Then they were driven to a nearby facility for physical exams
and showers.
   An hour before landing, Shaw fired twin braking rockets to drop
the shuttle out of orbit and start it on a fiery dive through the
atmosphere and into this desert air base 80 miles north of Los
Angeles.
   Mission Control lifted its curtain of silence to report the
successful firing. ``All parties here report a good deorbit burn;
all systems aboard Columbia are clean,'' Brian Welch, the control
center commentator, reported.
   Sonic booms cracked overhead as Columbia descended through a
clear sky and made its sweeping approach to runway 17 on Rogers Dry
Lake.
   The weather here was ideal, with clear skies, unlimited
visibility and mild temperatures.
   Although as many as half a million people have flocked to the
desert air base to watch previous shuttles land, Sunday's touchdown
was closed to the public because of the classified nature of the
mission.
   Most news about the flight has been blacked out on Pentagon
orders since an overhauled Columbia lifted off from Cape Canaveral
last Tuesday on its first flight in 3{ years.
   NASA was allowed to make only periodic statements that
spacecraft and crew were fine and to disclose the landing day and
then the time.
   Sources close to the project said the main goal of the flight
was the deployment of a sophisticated, 10-ton spy satellite
designed to snap highly detailed photographs of military
installations, troop movements and other targets of interest around
the world.
   It would help the United States verify Soviet compliance with
arms treaties, just as Russian satellites do over the United States
and Europe.
   Air Force Secretary Donald Rice confirmed Wednesday that a
satellite was deployed by the astronauts during their first day in
orbit, but he wouldn't discuss its purpose.
   To prepare for the trip back to Earth, Columbia commander Shaw
and pilot Richard Richards conducted a series of tests Saturday to
make certain the shuttle's computers and control jets were ready.
   In addition, mission specialists David Leestma, James Adamson
and Mark Brown stowed several experiments. Some of those tests were
believed to be connected with the ``Star Wars'' missile defense
project, while others involved determining how people can serve as
military observers from space.
   Columbia, the oldest shuttle, last flew in January 1986, landing
10 days before the Challenger explosion that killed the crew of
seven. After the accident NASA concentrated on making safety
modifications to the two newer shuttles, Discovery and Atlantis,
before turning attention to Columbia.
   Discovery and Atlantis each has made two space trips since
flights resumed last September.
   Columbia's return restored the shuttle flight to three vehicles
at a time when the launch rate is increasing, with three more
flights planned this year and nine in 1990. Another orbiter is
being built as a replacement for Challenger and is scheduled for
its first launch in early 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
