<DOCNO> AP890813-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 1359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Pierce-PenPals Bjt   08-13 1093</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pierce-Pen Pals, Bjt,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Secretary Got Tons of Letters Seeking Favors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The elderly man decked out in his Sunday best
posed proudly in the sunlight of a liquor store parking lot, hoping
the new Cabinet secretary would see a family resemblance in that
dignified profile.
   He wrote to Samuel R. Pierce Jr., the secretary of Housing and
Urban Development, that his mother's maiden name, too, was Pierce,
and she was from Arkansas.
   Pierce wrote back that he was from Virginia, and he was sure
they weren't kin.
   That letter was one of hundreds amassed by Pierce during the
eight years he served at HUD during the Reagan administration.
   Normally, a housing secretary's government files would be packed
off to the National Archives where they would receive scant
attention from historians, who would find sexier things to write
about than the tenure of a man who managed to remain in obscurity
throughout his time in office.
   But the $2 billion scandal of influence peddling and outright
theft that pervaded the department during the Pierce years has
changed all that. For a time during the past couple of weeks, the
crowd of reporters wanting to thumb through his files was so big
the public affairs office at HUD was taking reservations.
   One theme comes through the 48 boxes of speeches, letters,
bureaucratic jargon, ``grip 'n' grin'' photographs and mind-numbing
meeting minutes: Many of Pierce's pen pals were on the make.
   The vast majority wanted a job, some money, some time. They
tugged at every string they could find, a chance meeting at a
cocktail party, a handshake at a graduation ceremony, a family
friend in Congress, a seat in Congress, a seat at the Cabinet table.
   ``Dear Sam,'' began the 1981 letter from the late CIA Director
William Casey, trying to boost the fortunes of the son of a
deceased law partner.
   ``He's had a lot of experience in HUD, is a GS-14, is a proven
Republican, has philosophical credentials, and is the kind of
fellow who ought to be brought up from the bureaucracy into policy
work,'' Casey wrote of his friend's son.
   While the letters were as different as the people who composed
them, one thing all of the writers had in common was the
probability that they would be horrified at the thought of their
letters being dug out of the files by squads of chortling reporters.
   Finding the word ``CONFIDENTIAL'' across the top of a letter
discovered in these files now has an effect entirely opposite from
the one intended. Instead of ``keep this to yourself,'' it now
means ``Xerox me.''
   One such confidential memorandum was written in 1985 by Bernice
Williams, who at the time was director of the office of small and
disadvantaged business utilization.
   Ms. Williams had gotten into a spat with Deborah Gore Dean, who
was Pierce's executive assistant and now is a central figure in the
investigations of influence peddling. Pierce himself had said that
Ms. Dean enjoyed power and was not reluctant about using it to
flatten people in her path.
   While the files do not show what started the tiff, the incident
that brought it to a memo-writing fury was when Ms. Dean sent HUD
employees to Ms. Williams' office to cart away the furniture.
   After leading off with Ms. Dean's ``lack of sophistication and
immaturity,'' Ms. Williams went on to call her a liar and say, ``I
am not intimidated by your threats.''
   ``It is my hope that attitudinal vindictiveness be put aside in
the interest of effectively carrying out the secretary's goals and
objectives,'' Ms. Williams wrote.
   A formal reply to Ms. Williams was not found in the files, but
the fact that someone had marked her errors of spelling and grammar
gives some indication of what the tone must have been.
   Some of the papers in the files are dripping with irony, such as
the note Pierce sent to all HUD employees four years ago, urging
them to report any ``knowledge of waste, fraud and mismanagement.''
   ``The law provides broad protection from any reprisal being
taken against you for making such reports, and I give you my
personal assurance that I will not tolerate any such reprisal,''
Pierce wrote.
   On the back of Pierce's memo was typed a three-paragraph letter
from John Kieren, a HUD employee from Milwaukee, who blew the
whistle on wrongdoing in the department, got fired and spent 18
months in court to get his job back.
   ``My experience to report fraud, waste and mismanagement was a
horror story that I for one do not want to experience again,''
Kieren wrote.
   Other letters, now viewed with the 20-20 vision of hindsight,
might make their authors squirm.
   Pierce received a pair of thank-you letters from Charles Dempsey
and Paul Adams, both of whom have served as the agency's top
investigators and have been instrumental in exposing fraud and
waste in Pierce's department.
   ``I've told you previously how much I appreciated your support
and backing,'' Dempsey wrote in thanking Pierce for attending his
1985 retirement party as the department's inspector general.
   In his own note, Adams, who succeeded Dempsey, wrote that Pierce
made the event ``an evening neither Chuck nor the others who were
there will soon forget.''
   Some of the paper in the files gives a glimpse of what Pierce
himself was like. It seems that rarely did anyone he know
experience an illness or a death in the family that Pierce didn't
write a thoughtful note. In one case he wrote a letter of
condolence over the passing of ``Muffin,'' apparently a family's
pet.
   He also was mindful of the perks of his office, once inquiring
as to the free use of a restored presidential yacht, and demanding
in his extensive travels that he be accorded treatment befitting a
member of the president's Cabinet.
   In 1987, that trait nearly provoked an international incident at
Dulles Airport outside Washington, when Pierce's first-class
reservations on a flight to Paris were loused up.
   Pierce demanded an aisle seat in the first-class cabin, and an
airline employee, Sami Asfahani, went aboard to find a place for
the secretary to sit.
   ``In the course of events, Mr. Asfahani politely requested
members of a Saudi Arabian prince's party to rearrange their
seating so that I could secure the type of aisle seat I had
requested,'' Pierce wrote in a letter to the chairman of the board
of Pan American Airlines.
   ``Certain members of the prince's party overreacted in my
opinion,'' Pierce wrote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890813-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Taiwan     08-13 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Taiwan,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Shipping Company Loses Suit Against China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese court has ruled against the first
company from Taiwan to sue China, rejecting the claim that a
Taiwanese ship captain was intimidated into confessing to
smuggling, a pro-Beijing newspaper said Sunday.
   The Chinese-language newspaper Wen Wei Po said the Zhuhai
Intermediate People's Court on Saturday upheld the action of
Chinese customs officials and ordered the captain to pay $5,770 in
court costs.
   On March 6, a Chinese patrol boat seized the 1,963-ton Taiwanese
ship, Kuang Ta No. 2, near Hong Kong while it carried 31 crew
members and 4,760 cartons of cigarettes. Authorities released the
ship and crew several days later after captain Tsai Cheng-Hsiung
signed a confession that he was smuggling cigarettes.
   On April 11, the captain filed suit in Zhuhai, a Chinese port
about 40 miles southwest of Hong Kong. In the suit, the Kuang Hwa
Steam Ship Co. argued that the confession was signed under
``threat, tiring interrogation and the acute desire to release the
ship and crew.''
   It demanded $4.3 million in compensation and return of the
confiscated cigarettes.
   In its decision, the court rejected the company's argument that
the confession was extorted and that ship was in international
waters, the paper said.
   The Chinese had said the ship was in Chinese waters and its crew
planned to sell cigarettes to Chinese fishermen, a violation of
Chinese customs laws.
   Both the Nationalist government in Taipei and the Communist
government in Beijing have claimed to be the sole legitimate ruler
of China since 1949, when Communist forces drove the Nationalists
from the Chinese mainland.
   Recently, the two countries have relaxed restrictions on
Taiwanese visiting China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
