<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Grain     08-13 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Grain,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Farmers Get Easy Targets in Foreign Currency Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities have set relatively easy
targets for collective farms in an experiment designed to increase
grain production by paying for excess crops in convertible
currency, a newspaper said Sunday.
   The newspaper Labor said farms will be paid in dollars and other
world currencies for any high-quality grain they produce above
their average for 1981-85. The entire Soviet Union produced an
average of 180 million metric tons of grain during that period, far
less than the 210-211 million metric tons produced in the record
years of 1986 and 1987.
   Soviet authorities hope to stimulate domestic grain production
enough to reduce purchases of grain on the world market.
   Farms will be allowed to spend their hard currency as they wish
to obtain Western combines, food-processing equipment and other
items, the newspaper said. It was not clear if the farms could
choose to buy consumer goods.
   For peas and oil crops, the standard will be more difficult: the
average production of 1986-88, which were fairly good years.
   The two-year experiment will apply to collective and state
farms, the newspaper said. Authorities are still debating whether
to allow farmers on the new leasing program to join.
   American economist Marshall Goldman, commenting on the program
when it was proposed in June, said it could undercut the attempt to
convert farms to individual leaseholds.
   He predicted that collective farms seeking to break previous
records to obtain foreign currency will be unwilling to allow
individual farmers to break out on their own and lease part of the
farm's land.
</TEXT>
