<DOCNO> AP890813-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 1357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Beatlemania Bjt   08-13 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Beatlemania, Bjt,0974</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beatlemania is Back in the U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NXJ2</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINGRAD, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up a grimy staircase, through a dim
hallway and into a fourth-floor apartment, the Beatles are playing
and Kolya Vasin is preaching to a new generation the Beatles gospel
he accepted a quarter-century ago.
   From long ago and far away, the Beatles have had a grip on
Soviet youth, many of whom have lost faith in government and been
denied free access to religion.
   ``In your country, rock 'n' roll is just music,'' 19-year-old
Dima Vasiliev, a budding guitarist, told an American reporter.
``Here it's our soul, our heart. If there weren't rock and roll,
I'd be a Young Pioneer or Komsomol member,'' he said, referring to
Communist Party youth groups.
   ``The Beatles and what they did had a special effect on
Russia,'' said Vasin, 43, who describes himself as the Fab Four's
biggest Soviet fan and a ``Beatleologist.''
   With his long black beard, he could be mistaken for a Russian
Orthodox priest but for the Paul McCartney T-shirt he wears.
   ``Here, in a spiritual hunger, it's indescribable. It's a
substitute for religion,'' he said.
   Memorabilia is everywhere in Vasin's single grubby room, his
part of an apartment shared with two other families.
   It is a shrine, museum, dining room, living room and bedroom all
in one. Shelves from ceiling to floor are filled with Beatles books
and buttons. Walls are lined with ``A Hard Day's Night'' and
``Yellow Submarine'' posters and portraits of John, Paul, George
and Ringo.
   Like an eternal flame, a lamp atop the bookshelf continuously
throws orange light onto a photograph of John Lennon, who was
murdered in 1980. A small sign in front reads in English, ``Bless
You.''
   Vasin's proudest possession is a red, white and blue soccer
jersey he says Lennon wore. He said he got it through a friend of
singer Joan Baez.
   About a dozen teen-agers are sitting around a table as Beatles
music blares from a tape recorder.
   ``What's the name of that song?'' Vasin demands of one.
   The boy shrugs his shoulders.
   ``I'll have to call your mother about that tomorrow,'' Vasin
says jokingly.
   Vasiliev calls Vasin his spiritual father who ``taught us that
there's more than what school and parents taught us.''
   The teen-agers come by regularly to sing, dance and talk music.
   Vasin takes his Beatlemania seriously. He's been at it for 25
years, since a friend played him a tape recorded off British
Broadcasting Corp. radio.
   ``Something happened,'' he recalled. ``The words used were the
best. It was a high. Like God, sacred. A love hit me which I didn't
have before, only love for my mother.''
   Vasin, a painter, made himself an expert on Beatles trivia.
   He collected more than 15,000 Beatles photos, all of their
albums, bootlegged recordings and every scrap of paper about them
he could find.
   As ``I Saw Her Standing There,'' ``Help,'' and ``Norwegian
Wood'' resounded, he showed a reporter two Beatles
``encyclopedias'' he painstakingly compiled, including newspaper
clippings, photographs and poetry by or about the Beatles.
   Two articles serve as reminders that Beatles music and the
lifestyle they represented once were officially frowned on.
   ``These bugs can swiftly ignite the very darkest and primitive
passions,'' the satirical magazine Krokodil wrote in 1964. In the
same year, the head of the Soviet Composers Union titled his
condemnation of the Beatles in Literary Gazette, ``From the Life of
Bees and Dung Bugs.''
   Beatles records were banned, but Vasin and other Soviet Beatles
fans found other sources: foreign radio broadcasts and smuggled
albums. Still, just listening wasn't enough.
   By 1966, he recalled, ``People you would meet on the street
talked not about their illnesses or studies. The subject was the
Beatles. They were also the main subject of telephone calls.''
   The group's music spawned dozens of copycat groups in the Soviet
Union and gave birth to original Soviet rock, such as the group
Aquarium, which recently signed a U.S. recording contract and whose
lead singer, Boris Grebenshchikov, credits the Beatles with
changing his life.
   Fans held Beatles festivals, swapped tapes and photos, bought
their albums for exhorbitant prices on the black market, and some
sported their familiar haircuts and dressed like them in jackets
with round collars and no lapels. Vasin says some were arrested for
``hooliganism'' and ``anti-social behavior.''
   One teen-ager at Vasin's apartment said police fined his father
for playing Beatles music too loudly.
   The first positive press report about the group appeared in
1968, and Vasin recalls in a Soviet rock history book titled ``Back
in the U.S.S.R.'' that he was so happy he ran around Leningrad with
the article in his hand shouting, ``We've won!''
   More than two decades after they rocketed to the top of Western
music charts, the Beatles began to receive official recognition
here.
   The state record company Melodia in 1986 issued ``A Taste of
Honey'' and ``A Hard Day's Night.'' Some singles had been released
earlier without mentioning the group's name, because Melodia didn't
legally obtain permission to distribute them.
   Soviet Beatlemania has not gone unnoticed by the people who made
the music.
   In November, Melodia released ``Back in the U.S.S.R.,'' a
collecton of old rock 'n' roll songs McCartney recorded exclusively
for Soviet fans. He also paid tribute to them in January in a
phone-in show on the BBC's Russian service. He said he would like
to perform in the Soviet Union and that he admired Soviet fans for
following the Beatles despite official harassment.
   ``It didn't put us off, Russians. We love you madly,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
