<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 1238EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BradleyFinances     08-13 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bradley Finances,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Collects More than $2 Million in 1989 for Senate Re-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bill Bradley dipped into the money pools
of New York and Hollywood for more than $2 million in campaign
funds during the first seven months of the year even though there
is no GOP challenger in sight for his 1990 re-election bid.
   The effort vaulted the New Jersey Democrat into second place
among 1990 Senate incumbents for dollars raised this year _ behind
Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., and left him with more than $3.4 million.
   Actress Mary Tyler Moore, author Neil Simon, and ``Amadeus''
star Tom Hulce have written checks to the New Jersey Democrat's
re-election campaign.
   So have Warner Communications Chairman Steven Ross, MTV founder
Robert W. Pittman and Viacom International President and CEO Frank
J. Biondi Jr.
   Bradley's biggest money source from Jan. 1 to June 30 was a
$1,000-a-head New York City fund-raiser April 10 that netted $1.1
million, the most ever for a Bradley event.
   How do observers explain the nation appeal of Bradley?
   ``He's got sort of a magical nature about him that sort of
transcends politics,'' said Charlie Cook, who publishes The Cook
Political Report.
   ``His fund-raising prowess is extraordinary,'' said Tom Mann,
director of governmental studies at the Brookings Institution.
``He's one of the party's celebrities, a rising star.''
   Despite the contributions and Republican Gov. Thomas Kean's
recent assertion that Bradley is unbeatable, the campaign is taking
nothing for granted as it looks for an additional $6 million.
   ``Let's remember there is a governor's race in New Jersey,''
said Nick Donatiello, Bradley's campaign manager, in explaining the
lack of GOP candidates stepping forward so far.
   ``This is going to be an expensive Senate race,'' predicted
Donatiello. ``We would like to have $9 million to spend on the
campaign.''
   In 1984, Bradley spent $5.1 million to hold onto his seat,
compared with $956,000 spent by Republican Mary Mochary.
   Although Bradley has been mentioned for years as presidential
material, Donatiello put aside questions that Bradley might be
filling his coffers in anticipation of a 1992 White House bid.
   ``There's always the speculation,'' he said. ``We fully expect
to spend all the money we raise for the 1990 campaign on the '90
campaign.
   ``In order to run in New Jersey, you have to buy five Senate
races'' worth of media time _ for New Jersey, Connecticut,
Pennsylvania, Delaware and the most expensive media market of all,
New York, he said.
   Cook agreed.
   ``It's fairly prudent for a senator to run a decent amount of
TV. Secondly, think about what percentage of the U.S. population is
within those media markets. He's going to get a piece of the
country in terms of 1992,'' Cook said.
   Mann said Bradley has opted to be safe and at the same time
leave his political options open.
   ``Politicians always run scared, assume the worst and prepare
for it,'' said Mann. ``Therefore, you raise money if you're able to
as a way of discouraging whatever potential opposition may surface
and being ready to wage a serious campaign if you need to.''
   Looking at Bradley's ability to raise $4.3 million toward 1990,
Mann said: ``All of it fits in well with a potential run for the
presidency in 1992 or 1996 in any case. It seems very sensible even
if he hasn't decided if he's going to do that.''
</TEXT>
