<FIRST>r i AM-Canal-Glance     08-13 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canal-Glance,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Facts and Figures on the Panama Canal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Canal Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALBOA HEIGHTS, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some facts and figures on the
Panama Canal:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   COST _ The United States paid the French, who started work on
the canal, $40 million for rights and properties, then spent $387
million and ten years building it.
   VOLUME _ Nearly 262 million cubic yards of dirt and rock were
removed, enough to fill a train encircling the earth four times.
Dredges have dug out nearly 400 million more cubic yards to widen
the canal and keep it in good condition.
   UNSUNG HERO _ The Bucyrus steam shovel, 95-ton behemoths that
chomped out eight tons at a single scoop. The maximum number used
at one time: 68.
   FIRST TRANSIT, OCEAN-TO-OCEAN _ A canal workboat, the crane
barge Alexandre La Valley, Jan. 7, 1914.
   OFFICIAL OPENING _ Aug. 15, 1914, by the S.S. Ancon.
   PAYING TRANSITS _ More than 700,000. Total tons: more than 4
billion.
   AVERAGE TIME PER TRANSIT _ nine hours ocean-to-ocean.
   1914 COMMERCIAL RATES _ 90 cents per cargo ton, not raised until
1974.
   1989 COMMERCIAL RATES _ $1.83 per cargo ton; $1.46 per ton
unloaded.
   HIGHEST TOLL _ $109,653.60 paid in May 1989 by the Star
Princess, based on the amount of revenue-producing space aboard the
ship.
   LOWEST TOLL _ 36 cents, paid by 140-pound adventurer Richard
Halliburton when he swam the canal in the 1920s.
</TEXT>
