<FIRST>r w AM-EmpressII     08-13 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Empress II,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Moving To Outflank Opponents Of Its Nuclear Blast Simulator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barred from the Chesapeake Bay by Congress and
hounded by environmentalists in North Carolina, the Navy now is
trying to outflank its opponents as it eyes the Gulf of Mexico to
test whether ship electronics can withstand a nuclear blast in
space.
   ``We've started a very active public information and
availability program on the Gulf Coast,'' said Capt. W.E. Mahew,
manager of the Electromagnetic Pulse Radiation Environment
Simulator For Ships (Empress II) program.
   ``There was too much misinformation about what the program was
(when it was proposed for the Chesapeake Bay) and we were never
able to counter that information,'' he said. ``The guy who got
there first and told the story first was the only who was
believed.''
   Empress II consists of a barge-mounted, truncated cone of
antennas _ 128 feet high and 200 feet in diameter _ that surround a
pulser which can simulate the electromagnetic field that would be
generated by a nuclear blast in space.
   The system generates an electromagnetic pulse (EMP) that lasts
just 10 billionths of a second, but measures 50,000 volts per meter
at 100 meters from the barge in all directions. The EMP is fired at
passing ships to test the effectiveness of measures designed to
protect electronics systems from the EMP that would be generated by
a nuclear blast in space.
   While the Navy insists that the EMP generated by Empress II
poses no risk to the environment and that exclusion zones around
the barge will protect the electronic systems of nearby planes and
boats, it has had a difficult time thus far making its case.
   ``They just have not accurately assessed the impact of this on
human health, and what makes this particularly sad is that most of
the people being exposed are people in the service,'' said Andrew
Kimbrell, an attorney for the Foundation on Economic Trends.
   ``What we're seeing here is similar to the Army allowing those
soldiers to be exposed to the first nuclear blasts (after World War
II) and we know the high incidence of cancer that resulted there,''
he said.
   The foundation, a Washington-based watchdog group on emerging
technologies, has filed suit in U.S. District Court seeking to halt
Empress II tests off the coast of North Carolina until the Navy
adequately assesses the impact of the tests on human health and
animal life and on the electronic circuitry of nearby airplanes and
boats.
   The Navy began operating the Empress II off North Carolina in
the summer of 1988 after Congress enacted legislation prohibiting
it from operating in the Chesapeake Bay until the Navy demonstrated
that the tests could be conducted no where else with less
environmental impact.
   After the lawsuit was filed, the Navy chose a new site off North
Carolina and conducted an environmental assessment that concluded
the Empress II tests would have no significant environmental impact
at the new site. As soon as the 30-day period for public comment on
that assessment ended last month, the Navy resumed the Empress II
tests at the new site.
   In the meantime, letters went out July 26 announcing that the
Navy planned to begin the environmental assessment that could lead
to a new test site for Empress II about 20 miles off the
Alabama-Mississippi coast in the Gulf of Mexico.
   Mahew said the Navy needs the Gulf site because weather
conditions limit use of the North Carolina site to the summer
months. Originally, winter testing was to have been conducted in
the Chesapeake Bay. He said the Navy is planning 60 days of Empress
II tests in the Gulf annually between October and April.
   Long before plans for the Gulf site were announced, however,
Mahew said Navy personnel were meeting with state and local
officials and environmental groups in Alabama, Mississippi and
Louisiana in order to ``get ahead of the opposition.''
   ``We're laying it all out,'' he said. In four years of Naval and
independent research on the effects of EMP, he argues, ``We've
never been able to demonstrate any harm to human health, we've
never been able to demonstrate any harm to marine biota.''
   Despite those claims, and despite its best public relations
efforts, the Navy appears to be facing a long legal battle before
it can pursue its plan for year-round Empress II tests in the
Atlantic and the Gulf.
   ``I'm not an expert in the politics of the region,'' Kimbrell
said when asked to assess the prospects of the Navy winning the
public acceptance for Empress II in Alabama and Mississippi that
eluded it in Virginia and Maryland.
   ``However, they won't have any better legal atmosphere because
they're still going to have to comply with what is a federal law,
the National Environmental Policy Act,'' he said.
</TEXT>
