<FIRST>r a AM-Leland-Office     08-13 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-Office,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leland's Office is Somber After Wreckage Reported Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Ethiopia-Leland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends and colleagues, some in tears, streamed
into the downtown Houston office of Rep. Mickey Leland on Sunday
morning as news spread that wreckage of the Texas congressman's
plane was discovered in Ethiopia.
   U.S. officials said there were no survivors.
   ``This is a very difficult time for Houston. We have lost one of
our most important leaders, and I've lost a very good friend,''
said Rep. Mike Andrews, his voice breaking.
   Andrews, like Leland a Houston Democrat, was among the first to
arrive at the office after word came that supporters' hopes that
Leland and his entourage had somehow survived since Monday had
proven futile.
   ``I know our prayers and thoughts are with his family, his wife,
their young son, and soon-to-be new baby,'' Andrews said. ``Mickey
Leland was a very special person. I will miss him very much.''
   Leland's wife, Alison, was in seclusion Sunday morning at their
Houston home and planned to make a statement later in the day, a
spokesman said.
   Meanwhile, Leland staff members were closeted in his
eighth-floor offices at a downtown Houston skyscraper. People could
be seen hugging and crying in the office. Volunteers delivered
coffee and soft drinks to aides who had kept a vigil at the office.
   ``It's very somber, very sad. They are still in shock,'' said
Kippy Caraway, who was helping Leland's staff.
   State Rep. Harold Dutton, a friend of Leland's since childhood,
was in the office off and on all night, and was there when the call
came in that the wreckage had been found.
   ``We got a call from our Washington office around 6,'' Dutton
said, his voice wavering. ``As you can well imagine, it's pretty
somber up there. A lot of people are calling in and expressing
their sentiments.''
   Paul Joseph, a family friend and consultant for food-lifts to
African countries, said: ``Mickey Leland has made the supreme
sacrifice as a humanitarian. Only good can come from him.''
   ``We've lost a real leader, and real leaders in our political
world are few and far between,'' said Bill Ramsey, a Democratic
Party consultant and friend who had been frequently at Leland's
office in the past week.
   ``I guess everyone was hoping it would not come out this way,''
said John Odom, a Leland friend and Democratic candidate for
attorney general.
   ``At a personal level, I've lost a friend. But more than that,
he was an international leader, and it will be difficult if not
impossible to replace him,'' Odom said.
</TEXT>
