<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     08-13 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defiance Campaign to Widen as Government Reels From Power Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the government distracted
by a damaging leadership struggle, anti-apartheid activists said
Sunday the next phases of their nationwide defiance campaign wil
include challenges to segregation of beaches and schools.
   The defiance campaign, launched Aug. 2 when blacks and Indians
peacefully sought treatment at segregated white hospitals, has been
condemned by the National Party government as an attempt to provoke
confrontation and violence.
   Since Friday, however, top government officials have been
preoccupied by a dispute between President P.W. Botha and Education
Minister F.W. de Klerk, who heads the National Party and is
expected to succeed Botha after the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections.
   Botha, 73, brought the long-running rift into the open when he
announced Friday he had not been consulted about de Klerk's planned
meeting on Aug. 28 with Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda, a
prominent critic of South Africa's racial policies.
   De Klerk conferred with his Cabinet colleagues on Saturday and
reportedly obtained full backing from them heading into a formal
Cabinet meeting with Botha on Monday.
   Political writers said de Klerk was likely to demand that Botha
stop interfering in government affairs pending his retirement next
month. Botha could accept the ultimatum, quit immediately, or try
to fire de Klerk and other ministers, newspapers suggested.
   In any case, Foreign Minister Pik Botha has said he and de Klerk
will keep their appointment with Kaunda.
   The Sunday Star of Johannesburg described Botha as ``an unguided
missile trying to inflict maximum damage before the September
elections'' and warned in an editorial that his ``childish rage''
could jeopardize important diplomatic initiatives.
   City Press, the country's largest-selling newspaper for blacks,
headlined its lead editorial Sunday: ``In the name of God, P.W.
Botha, please go!''
   Groups affiliated with the Mass Democratic Movement, a coalition
organizing the protests, said they planned to defy beach
segregation laws in the port city of Durban and demand integration
of ``whites-only'' schools in racially mixed inner-city
neighborhoods.
   Organizers were quoted by the City Press and other papers as
saying they did not want to reveal too many details at this stage,
but they said a mass rally was planned for next Sunday at one of
the remaining whites-only beaches in Durban.
   Plans also were announced for a meeting Thursday in Johannesburg
to launch a campaign called ``All schools for all people'' to
protest segregation of government schools. The Sunday Star said
blacks living in central Johannesburg will be encouraged to take
their children to under-utilized white schools near their homes.
   Several inner-city neighborhoods have became racially mixed in
recent years as the government eased enforcement of residential
segregation laws. But black children in these areas must travel
long distances to outlying black townships if they wish to attend
public schools.
   In another development, 11 white policemen were scheduled to
appear in court Monday to face armed robbery charges after they
allegedly robbed black entrepreneurs in several townships near
Johannesburg.
   Police have released only a few details about the case and said
that ``senstive'' investigations were continuing following the
arrests last week.
   Local press reports said the suspects, all in their 20s, had
targeted the owners of licensed and unlicensed taverns in the
townships and had stolen at least $40,000 over a four-month period.
The constables reportedly told their victims they were members of
the White Wolves, a name which has surfaced in recent months in
connection with acts of terror by white right-wing extremists.
   Police officials have insisted there is no evidence the White
Wolves actually exists.
</TEXT>
