<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Politics     08-13 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Politics,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa to Meet Kiszczak, May Be Prime Minister Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Sunday
he plans to meet communist Prime Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak in
the near future, and a Solidarity official said Walesa might
himself be willing to head Poland's next government.
   In comments relayed by an aide in the Baltic port of Gdansk,
Walesa said, ``I do not want to, nor should I be prime minister. I
have my own candidates.''
   But Senator Jaroslaw Kaczynski, Walesa's envoy in talks with two
minor parties on formation of a Solidarity-led coalition
government, said Sunday of Walesa, ``it is true he is considering''
becoming prime minister.
   The opposition newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza had raised the
possibility of Walesa's becoming prime minister last week, and
another Solidarity lawmaker, Senator Aleksander Paszynski, said it
was raised in talks with the other parties.
   Walesa left his home in Gdansk Sunday afternoon for Warsaw,
where on Monday he was expected to take part in coalition talks
with political leaders of the other parties in parliament.
   Replying to the appeal of newly elected Prime Minister Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak, who announced Saturday he wanted to meet Walesa
``as soon as possible,'' Walesa said he too wants such a meeting.
   ``I will meet with Gen. Kiszczak in the nearest future ... We
cannot avoid difficult topics,'' Walesa said, according to the aide.
   Kiszczak was elected prime minister Aug. 2, but his efforts to
form a government ran into trouble four days later when Walesa
announced he would oppose any government formed by the longtime
interior minister.
   Solidarity senator Kaczynski said Walesa authorized him to
conduct talks with the Democratic Party and the Peasants Party, two
small parties that hold the balance of power in the parliament
because Solidarity and the communists each have less than 50
percent of the seats.
   The talks that began Thursday continued through the weekend at
an undisclosed site, Kaczynski said, speaking by telephone from his
home in Warsaw.
   ``They are conducted amid different difficulties with good will
on all three sides,'' he said. The Democrats and the Peasants were
leaning toward the idea of a coalition with Solidarity, he said,
but that there was no way to say where those talks would lead.
   Peasant Party deputies have said voters reacted badly to the
choice of Kiszczak as prime minister, the election of Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski to the new post of president and the selection of former
prime minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski as the new head of the
communist party.
   The reshuffle at the top leaves the impression among voters that
nothing has changed despite Solidarity's victory at the polls in
June, when union-backed candidates swept all 161 seats open to the
opposition in the 460-member Sejm and 99 of 100 seats in the newly
created Senate.
   ``If one recognizes that these elections were really won by the
opposition, then it should be ready to take over the government,''
said Solidarity member Paszynski in a telephone interview.
   Walesa was a ``logical'' candidate for prime minister, even
though he is not an expert on the economy, he said.
   The political stalemate at the top echelons of power and growing
frustration over steep price hikes Aug. 1 and soaring inflation has
frustrated Poles, prompting a number of work stoppages in protest
over economic chaos.
   Solidarity says the new government must have public support in
order to be able to rule _ backing that a communist-led coalition
will be unable to achieve.
   Communist leaders have repeatedly urged Solidarity to join a
so-called ``grand coalition'' in which the opposition would be
offered several ministries, but Solidarity has declined, saying
that option would change nothing.
   But the prospect of a non-communist led government appears to
have disconcerted Poland's main Warsaw Pact ally.
   A Soviet Foreign Ministry official in Moscow on Friday
criticized attempts to use the formation of the Polish government
``for destabilizing the sitution in the country,'' according to the
Tass news agency.
</TEXT>
