<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-13 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing the nearly 1,000 magicians who
gathered for a weekend convention was no easy trick.
   There are nearly as many magicians as there are residents during
the 52nd annual Abbott Magic Get-Together in Colon.
   ``We don't have any hotels in town,'' said housing coordinator
Debbie Bordner. Some magicians end up staying in Battle Creek or
Kalamazoo, 35 to 40 miles away from the hometown of Abbott Magic
Co., which organizes the gathering.
   Over the years, many have found lodging with Herman and Helmine
Oldenberg, both 72, who have opened their home to as many as 20 of
the visiting tricksters.
   ``We only have one shower so they have to line up for a
shower,'' Oldenberg said.
   ``And I don't understand our hot water heater,'' Mrs. Oldenberg
added. ``It never runs out of water.''
   Last year, Oldenberg said, we had six upstairs, three in the
basement, two on the patio, two in the camper trailer, four in the
truck camper and three in their own camper out front.'' This year,
they are housing five.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KNIGHTSTOWN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The DeMarco family hasn't run into any
big problems in the first month of a covered-wagon journey from
Ohio to California, but the five children are getting a bit
restless.
   ``Every day (2{-year-old) Martina will ask, `Are we going to
California today? Are we there yet?' The kids don't have the same
conception of time and distance,'' said Pam DeMarco.
   She and her husband, Thomas-Angelo, passed through Knightstown,
30 miles east of Indianapolis, last week in their tractor-drawn
Conestoga-style wagon, chosen to symbolize their search fo a better
life.
   The DeMarcos, recently of Kipton, Ohio, built the covered wagon
for cheap transportation and as a protest against 20th century
lifestyles.
   ``A lot of people come up and say, `I envy you,''' said DeMarco,
37. ``They say to my wife, `You can leave your refrigerator and
washing machine and not know where you're going to stay.' Hey, a
quarter million people went west in covered wagons.''
   They hope to reach Southern California, where they have friends,
by Christmas. They hope to buy a farm one day.
   An Air Force veteran and woodworker by trade, DeMarco says his
business was failing last year and he was forced to vacate a home
he had been restoring. Mrs. DeMarco, an American history buff,
suggested the family move west by covered wagon, and they pieced
the vehicle together from an old farm wagon and other salvaged
parts.
   ``People come up and have some innate sense of why we're doing
this,'' DeMarco said. ``They say things like, `You must love
America.' Yeah, that's right.''
</TEXT>
