<FIRST>r w AM-Bennett-Drugs     08-13 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett-Drugs,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Says Drug Users, Not Government, Blame for Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug users, rather than failed government
policies, are to blame for the spread of drugs throughout society,
drug policy director William J. Bennett said Sunday.
   He also defended the Reagan administration's efforts to combat
drugs, including former First Lady Nancy Reagan's ``Just Say No''
campaign.
   Bennett by law must forward a new national strategy for fighting
drugs to Congress by Sept. 5. It is expected to call for a major
boost in federal spending and emphasize both tougher penalties for
individual drug use and mandatory treatment for addicts.
   Bennett was asked on CBS' ``Face the Nation'' if his approach
marks a reversal from the Reagan administration policy, which cut
funds for treatment and emphasized drug interdiction and arrests of
kingpins.
   The $21 billion spent fighting drugs during the Reagan
administration ``wasn't wasted, and it wasn't all wrong. ... ''
said Bennett. ``There were some real successes during the Reagan
era.
   ``I don't think anyone can deny that drugs are pervasive
throughout much of America,'' said Bennett, but recent statistics
indicate that casual drug use is down.
   ``Although some people like to criticize the educational efforts
and the first lady's efforts, they obviously have had some
effect,'' said Bennett, who as Reagan's education secretary
published a booklet on how to keep drugs out of schools.
   ``We are shifting strategy, but let's remember we have not had
the opportunity before to have a comprehensive look,'' said Bennett.
   ``The government may not have been as effective ... (or) as
smart as it should have been. ... But it's the people who are
taking drugs that are causing these tragedies, not the
government,'' he said.
   Asked if he would recommend raising taxes for the drug fight,
Bennett replied, ``Don't think we need taxes.''
   But he insisted, ``The money will be there. We will put our
cards on the table. We will suggest what we want to do and we will
propose spending more money. Then we will see what the Congress
wants to do.
   ``It means making some difficult choices,'' he said.
   Bennett, citing reports of bootleg sales of methadone by addicts
to buy crack, said drug treatment programs need ``much more
accountability.''
   Without it, Bennett warned, ``at some point the American people
will say, `The heck with it.'
   ``The more I've seen of (treatment), the more impressed I am by
the need for efforts in prevention. It's terrible to get into this
business, it's very hard to get out of it,'' he said.
   He scoffed at the notion that research can find a way to end
people's cravings for drugs.
   ``We're not going to uncover anything in a laboratory that ...
we can put in a pill and give it to somebody and they're not going
to want drugs anymore,'' said the onetime philosophy professor.
   And despite five months of ``conscientious'' study of the
issues, Bennett said he has found ``no magic bullet.''
   His recommendations won't be like ``Batman (coming) through the
transom saying, `Here it is, and it's over,''' Bennett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
