<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     08-13 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Junta Announces Economic Reform Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's new military leaders on Sunday
announced an economic reform program that includes a 20 percent cut
in government spending and possible decreases in government
subsidies of consumer goods.
   Col. Salah Din Mohamed Karrar, a member of the 15-member council
in charge of the economy, said in an interview with the Sudan News
Agency that he was optimistic Sudan would be able to reach a loan
agreement with the International Monetary Fund soon.
   Improving Sudan's faltering economy, which is burdened by a $13
billion foreign debt and an exhausting civil war in the south, has
been one of the main targets of the new regime, which took power in
a military coup June 30.
   Karrar said the Finance Ministry had ordered government units to
cut spending by 20 percent, but he did not specify how much money
that would save.
   One of the junta's first acts was to cut the Cabinet from 30 to
22 ministers.
   Karrar also said that government subsidies to some of the main
consumer goods would be ``reconsidered,'' but he did not say which
commodities would be affected.
   The ousted elected government of Sadek el-Mahdi had budgeted
$183 million for subsidies this fiscal year.
   Karrar said he was optimistic Sudan would reach agreement with
the IMF next month without affecting the welfare of Sudanese
people. He gave no details.
   In February 1986, the IMF declared Sudan ineligible for further
loans for defaulting on debt payments. U.S. economic assistance was
halted in January because the Khartoum government was late in
paying off loans.
</TEXT>
