<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 1642EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SecondhandCrack     08-13 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Secondhand Crack,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Wonder If Crack Smoke Killed 10 Infants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical examiners in Philadelphia are trying
to determine whether 10 infants died over the last three years as a
result of inhaling secondhand crack smoke from adults. The 10 all
had chemical evidence of cocaine in their blood.
   The coroner, Haresh G. Mirchandani, came up with the theory
after the April 6 death of a 10-month-old girl named Tasha. Testing
showed there was cocaine in the her blood, some of which had gotten
there the night before her death.
   Mirchandani said the baby died after apparently inhaling smoke
from crack, a highly addictive form of cocaine, generated by her
mother and other adults in the house.
   The deaths of Tasha and nine other babies might show, according
to the medical examiner's theory, that children are highly
susceptible to serious illness and death from breathing in crack
smoke when the drug is smoked by adults around them.
   Mirchandani stressed last week that more research was needed
before his theory could be proven.
   Mirchandani's study involved the cases of six girls and four
boys _ ranging in age from 28 days to 10 months _ who died in the
city in the last three years.
   Each infant had either cocaine or its chemical residue in their
blood, tissue, or organs, the study found.
   Several babies had parents, siblings, or baby sitters who used
crack. Several slept in small, poorly ventilated rooms in crowded
row houses. In some instances, police or residents said they saw
lingering clouds of crack smoke or discarded crack vials in the
homes, according to the investigation.
   Mirchandani said the investigation started the day after Tasha's
death. He refused to provide the full names or addresses of the
infants or their relatives.
   An autopsy performed on Tasha's body revealed small amounts of
active cocaine as well as the drug's residue. Mirchandani
determined that the presence of the active cocaine, which is
usually broken down by the body in two hours, showed the baby had
been exposed to it shortly before she died _ ``only a few hours
before death,'' Mirchandani said.
   The residue indicated exposure to the drug of a long-term
nature, he said.
   Mirchandani visited the baby's 22-year-old mother May 1.
   ``She admitted being a crack addict,'' he said. She ``said she
used cocaine before and during the pregnancy.''
   Mirchandani said the mother was not breast-feeding the child.
She had not put the drug in the child's food or milk, and there was
no sign the child could have found the drug lying around and eaten
it.
   Recent studies of the dangers of the passive inhalation of
cigarette smoke led Mirchandani to the possibility that the same
was true of the passive inhalation of crack smoke. He said even
though the mother ``said she didn't smoke around the baby,'' the
child's room was not well-ventilated and other adults addicted to
the drug smoked it in the house.
   Similar cases in Philadelphia and New York City supported the
doctor's theory, he said.
   ``Cocaine can be toxic at any dose, and is proven to be
dangerous and deadly in even small doses ... even in adults,'' he
said. ``I would expect a much heightened toxicity for infants. It's
common sense. Something that is toxic for adults ... would be even
more toxic for an infant.''
</TEXT>
