<FIRST>r a AM-GreenRiver     08-13 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green River,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>At Least a Month's More Work in Murder Investigation, Task Force
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Green River Task Force is a month or more
away from completing a study of thousands of documents, videotapes
and other possessions of a former law student called a suspect in
the killings of 40 young women.
   ``There's more of it here than even I thought there was,'' Capt.
Bob Evans, commander of the King County Police task force, said of
the material seized from William Jay Stevens II, 38.
   Asked if police had found anything to connect Stevens with any
of the Green River victims, Evans replied, ``Not yet.''
   Stevens denies he is the killer. ``People should know the fact
that I have never hurt anyone in my life,'' he said in a statement
released earlier through his attorney.
   Stevens has not been charged with any violent crimes, including
the Green River killings, a series of slayings from 1982 to 1984,
mostly of prostitutes in Seattle and Portland, Ore. The case takes
its name from the stream south of Seattle river where the bodies of
the first victims were found.
   Police have blamed the deaths of 40 young women and the
disappearance of eight others on the serial killer.
   Stevens is in the King County Jail, serving a one-year sentence
for a 1979 burglary and additional time for escape.
   He's due to be released Sept. 25, but Evans said he doubts the
12-member task force will be finished by then with analyzing the
thousands of items in 55 boxes and bags taken in a July 12 search
of the home of Stevens' parents and a rental house Stevens used as
a student in Spokane.
   Police would have no hold on Stevens after Sept. 25, Evans said.
   ``We're still going through the paperwork and expect to be doing
that for another month or so,'' Evans said.
   ``There's been nothing so far to diminish our interest or to
indicate we should feel any more strongly about him.''
   Stevens walked away from a work-release program in Seattle in
1981, and wasn't apprehended until January of this year, when it
was learned he was living at his parents' home in Spokane and
attending Gonzaga University Law School.
   Among the possessions seized by the task force were police
badges and paraphernalia.
   Investigators have suspected the Green River killer could be a
police officer or someone posing as one.
   
   In an affidavit filed to support a search warrant in the case,
some people who knew Stevens said he liked pornography, frequented
prostitutes and carried photographs of mutilated women.
   Among items seized in the search were 1,800 videotapes. A sample
of the videotapes show they ``ranged from TV shows to hard-core
pornography,'' Evans said.
   He said he will have the task force look at all the tapes ``only
if I have to. I don't want to, but if necessary, I will do that.''
   Besides the tapes, the material includes massive amounts of
paperwork, much of it receipts and personal documents. Evans said
detectives have followed up much of their reading with interviews,
but he had no estimate of the number conducted.
   Evans said investigators are seeking both possible links to the
killings and alibis for Stevens.
   ``We're working very, very hard to prove that he's someone not
of interest to us,'' he said.
   Detectives are looking at people other than Stevens, but Evans
declined to say whom.
   ``There always have been other people we have been checking out
and there will be until there are no leads to follow.''
</TEXT>
