<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Drench Kansas, East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms drenched sections of Kansas and much
of the Eastern Seaboard on Sunday, and rain fell on much of the
rest of the nation. Low-temperature records were tied in three
Southern cities.
   Downpours in southwest Kansas overnight dumped more than 4
inches of rain at Coldwater and Offerle. Light rain continued into
the afternoon.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms hit much of the Atlantic
Coast, with the heaviest rain over Florida and southern New
England. Up to 3 inches of rain soaked Massachusetts in the 24
hours ending at midafternoon Sunday.
   Thunderstorms also extended from northern Oklahoma to
west-central Texas, and over the northern Plains and upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Fort Myers, Fla., tied its record low for the date at 70
degrees; Meridian, Miss., tied its 62-degree record and New Orleans
tied its 68-degree mark.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Lompoc, Calif., to 107 in Needles and Palm Springs,
Calif. Sunday's low for the Lower 48 states was 30 degrees at
Truckee, Calif.
   Monday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the Gulf Coast states to the Great Lakes region and northern
Atlantic Coast states; and scattered showers and thunderstorms from
Montana to Utah and Colorado.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast,
in the 70s from the upper Mississippi Valley to northern New
England, in the lower 90s across southern Texas and southern New
Mexico and west of the Rockies and above 100 degrees in the desert
Southwest.
