<FIRST>r a AM-AqueductRepairs     08-13 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aqueduct Repairs,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Repairing Storm-Ravaged LA Aqueduct Get Break From Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLANCHA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers repairing the flood-damaged
aqueduct that supplies millions of Southern Californians with water
got a break in the weather Sunday, but expected to be on the job
two more weeks.
   Some 30 workers using bulldozers and other heavy equipment
labored under sunny skies to scoop tons of mud, rocks and other
storm debris out of the Los Angeles Aqueduct in Inyo County about
180 miles north of Los Angeles.
   ``They're continuing right along today, making good progress,''
said Los Angeles Department of Water and Power spokeswoman Dorothy
Jensen.
   A two-mile stretch of the aqueduct was buried when a flash flood
hurled tons of debris down upon it Tuesday. Then a storm Thursday
buckled a 1,000-foot stretch of the aqueduct's concrete lining.
   The aqueduct carries water from streams in the eastern Sierra
Nevada range to Los Angeles and other Southern California
communities.
   Two 30-person teams were each working 12-hour shifts, and
repairs were expected to take two weeks, the spokeswoman said.
   The city, which gets 75 percent of its water from the aqueduct,
wasn't expected to experience shortages in the meantime, but water
officials urged residents to voluntarily conserve.
   A series of intense, widely scattered storms deluged parts of
San Diego, Imperial, San Bernardino, Riverside, Mono and Inyo
counties throughout most of last week before moving into Nevada.
   Until the aqueduct is fixed, the water department will provide
Los Angeles with water by drawing supplies from reservoirs south of
the broken part of the aqueduct and making extra purchases from the
Southern California Metropolitan Water District.
   Ms. Jensen said the damage was the worst since similar storms
ravaged the aqueduct in 1968.
</TEXT>
