<FIRST>r a AM-WildernessProgram     08-13 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wilderness Program,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Survival Program Faces Licensing, Legal Challenges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wilderness survival program for troubled
teens is fighting for its own life after running afoul of state
officials and a teen-age girl who claims she was kidnapped and
abused by the program's operators.
   Challenger Foundation II is designed to quell rebellious
behavior and build confidence in teen-agers by forcing them to
confront their problems in the setting of the rugged southern Utah
desert.
   During their first three days in the desert, for example, they
may eat only wild plants that they pick or animals and insects that
they catch.
   The state attorney general's office says such a program amounts
to therapy, which Challenger II lacks a license to provide.
   In addition, a judge has ruled that Challenger operators
violated the civil rights of 17-year-old Elizabeth Zasso of Mt.
Kisco, N.Y., by abducting her from a dentist's office and forcing
her into the program at her father's request.
   Ms. Zasso is suing the program and its operators for $230
million, and a big award could put the school out of business.
   Challenger is threatened with further legal action from the
state attorney general unless the operators can demonstrate that
participating teens are provided adequate food, water and clothing,
as well as such necessities as toilet paper and sleeping bags.
   Program founder Stephen Cartisano, a former Air Force special
forces sergeant billed in ads as a ``real-life Rambo,'' has filed a
countersuit charging the state with harassment.
   Several state officials say they will decide this week whether
Challenger must obtain a license as a therapeutic care provider to
continue operation. Currently, the program's counselors don't have
the training required for such a license.
   Cartisano, who was in southern Utah over the weekend, did not
return telephone calls to his office in Provo.
   Ms. Zasso's attorneys didn't respond to a telephone request for
comment.
   The company's ads promise that for $12,500 per teen, Challenger
``stops self-destructive behavior and places parents back in
control.'' Its detractors say the 63-day survival program is cruel
and dangerous.
   In the first stage of the program, the teens drink stream water
they must purify with chemicals and substitute sagebrush for toilet
paper.
   During the two latter stages, the participants' diet included
oatmeal, lentils, cheese, meat, raisins and other foods provided by
Challenger.
   During stage three, each 12-member group is given two wooden
handcarts which they pull across about 130 miles of desert,
emulating Mormon handcart pioneers who settled Utah in the 19th
century.
   A graduate of the program, Krista Palmer, 15, of Provo said it
helps youths overcome social and behavioral problems by building
confidence and self esteem.
   ``It wasn't my idea of a picnic. It was a hard program,'' said
Ms. Palmer. ``It helped me realize my potential, to see what I
could do physically, emotionally and spiritually.''
   She said that before her mother ordered her into the program
last May, she was shy and lacked confidence. Now, she said she
feels confident talking with strangers and peers, and she's
confident that she can boost her grades beyond her current
C-average.
   She also believes she is better able to resist the temptation of
drug abuse.
   Before the experience, ``My self-esteem was low enough I didn't
think I was worth enough to say no. I was headed for the drugs and
alcohol.''
   In her lawsuit, Ms. Zasso said she was working as a dental
assistant in Mt. Kisco on June 15 when Challenger employees lured
her into a dark hallway, subdued her and hustled her to a nearby
airport for a flight to southern Utah.
   Ms. Zasso had left home to live with her boyfriend's family and
had refused to return home.
   She said she was subjected to a strip search and then forced to
walk as much as 18 miles at a time without food and clean water.
The suit also alleges that she was denied medical treatment for a
concussion.
   She remained in the program for 42 days until 3rd District Judge
Dennis Frederick, who is considering the suit, found her rights had
been violated and ordered her release.
   Zasso praised the program in a videotaped interview conducted by
Challenger employees in the desert, but she later testified that
she feared she would be forced repeat the program if she didn't
tell the counselors what they wanted to hear.
</TEXT>
