<FIRST>r p AM-TexasElectionRdp     08-13 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texas Election Rdp,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP, Democrats Square Off in Race for Wright Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican physician was the highest vote-getter
in a special election to replace Jim Wright in Congress, but the
Democrat who will face him in a runoff predicted victory in the
heavily Democratic 12th District.
   Dr. Bob Lanier garnered 21,978 ballots, or 39 percent of the
vote, in Saturday's special election, but Democrat Pete Geren was
elated about his 32 percent showing _ 17,751 votes _ in the
district that encompasses most of Fort Worth.
   Geren received a ringing endorsement from Wright, who had
expressed no favorite in the primary.
   ``I want to ask all of you to redouble your efforts because
here's a man I want to be my successor,'' the popular Wright told
supporters at a Fort Worth party for Geren. ``He is steeped in the
traditions of our state and country.''
   Democrat Jim Lane finished third in the race with 22 percent of
the vote, the only other candidate to garner more than 3 percent.
   ``Well, the Democrats won tonight,'' Geren, an attorney, told
cheering supporters late Saturday. ``It took us four candidates to
do it, but when you total it up, we got nearly 60 percent of the
vote. I call that a victory.''
   Wright resigned the seat June 30 after an ethics investigation
uncovered 69 instances of alleged house violations.
   In other election results, a Dallas government redistricting
plan that supporters said would foster minority representation
passed by a 2-to-1 margin. And Dallas Area Rapid Transit officials
won a significant battle when voters in four of five Dallas suburbs
decided to retain the agency.
   Because no one in the eight-candidate race to replace Wright
received a majority of the votes, a runoff is necessary. Gov. Bill
Clements will set a date after election results are certified.
   Lanier, host of a nationally syndicated TV health show, ``60
Second Housecall,'' pointed to his success in a district
traditionally dominated by Democrats, and Wright in particular.
   Wright first won election in 1955 and was re-elected 17 times in
the next 34 years, often with token or no opposition. He received
88 write-in votes in Saturday's special election.
   However, Ronald Reagan and George Bush carried the district in
the last three presidential elections.
   ``Remember, now it's halftime,'' Lanier told supporters Saturday
night. ``Take a breather, go to church, come back on Monday and
let's get after it.''
   In an emotionally charged referendum, Dallas voters
overwhelmingly approved a proposal to reorganize the city council,
ostensibly to equalize voting power between whites and minorities.
The proposal received 41,456 votes to 20,823 against.
   However, an analysis by The Dallas Morning News of voting
patterns in Saturday's election showed that more than 85 percent of
those who voted in the city's predominantly minority districts
opposed the plan. The plan passed citywide because of overwhelming
support from white voters.
   The so-called ``10-4-1'' plan calls for the addition of two
single districts and four quadrant representatives, leaving the
mayor as the only at-large member of the city council.
   Opponents, who had their own plan, argued that adding seats
would dilute minority strength.
   A lawsuit challenging the current 8-3 plan is scheduled to be
heard Sept. 5 by U.S. District Judge Jerry Buchmeyer, who also is
reviewing the 10-4-1 plan.
   The five suburban elections were crucial to about one-fifth of
the Dallas transit agency's sales tax income, and to the fate of a
regional transportation system.
   Voters in Carrollton, Rowlett, Irving and Plano decided by
margins of 59 percent or more to stay in DART. Coppell rejected
DART by a 20-vote margin, but officials there said a recount is
likely.
   In June, DART approved a $2.45 billion plan to crisscross the
metropolitan area with 66 miles of light rail by 2010. The plan
also called for 18 miles of rail connecting downtown to the
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport and 37 miles of bus and car
pool lanes for suburban commuters.
</TEXT>
