<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Lebanon     08-13 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel, SLA Captured Assistant to Hezbollah Car Bomber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli security forces and South Lebanese Army
militiamen captured a Lebanese man who allegedly assisted a suicide
car bomb attack that wounded five Israeli soldiers, the army said
Sunday.
   The 28-year-old man, identified as a mercenary of the Moslem
fundamentalist Hezbollah group, was captured in south Lebanon on
Wednesday, the day of the car bombing attack, but the army withheld
the information until Sunday, an army statement said.
   The army would not give his name, and a military spokesman would
not say if the man was being held by Israeli or SLA security forces.
   Five Israeli soldiers were wounded, one critically, when a car
packed with 550 pounds of explosives blew up near a convoy of
Israeli and SLA troops.
   The Shiite Moslem group Hezbollah claimed responsibility for the
bombing and released a videotape showing the driver, Sheikh Assad
Biro, who killed himself in the attack.
   There was no immediate word from Hezbollah on the arrest.
   The army statement said the purported assistant was a resident
of the village of Markaba, about a mile from the Israeli border. It
said he was recruited by Hezbollah in Beirut to organize attacks in
Israel's self-declared security zone in southern Lebanon.
   The alleged assistant let Biro stay the night before the bombing
at his home in the security zone, the statement said. It said the
two tried unsuccessfully to plant an explosive device that day.
   The man helped Biro get to the area where the car bomb detonated
but was not in the car at the time, the army said.
   The security zone is a six- by 10-mile-wide strip in southern
Lebanon where Israel maintained a military force after the
withdrawal of most of its troops from Lebanon in 1985.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is a fundamentalist Iranian-backed
Shiite faction in Lebanon that is considered to be the umbrella
organization for extremist groups holding foreign hostages in
Lebanon. Sixteen foreigners are being held, including eight
Americans.
