<FIRST>r a AM-VictoryDay 1stLd-Writethru a0706 08-13 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Victory Day, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0706,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rhode Island Victory Day Holiday Again Provokes Outcry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `Japan surrendered...,' to CORRECT date to May
sted March.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Japanese-Americans are trying to
change the name of Rhode Island's Victory Day holiday because they
say the popular name _ ``V-J Day'' for ``Victory in Japan'' _ is
racist.
   The holiday Monday is still celebrated only in Rhode Island,
where by tradition it creates a long weekend when virtually
everything shuts down and people head to the beach.
   This year, the Japan Society of Rhode Island has hired lawyers
to try to change the name.
   ``Unfortunately, the name Victory Day has caused persistent use
of the appellation `V-J Day' by the public, by the press,
businesses, state offices,'' said one of the lawyers, Jennifer Wood.
   Wood declined to say how the group might pursue a lawsuit, but
said she has asked Attorney General James E. O'Neil's office to
press for a name change or a way to force people to use the
holiday's official name.
   Thomas Connell, spokesman for O'Neil, said the attorney general
cannot ``require the citizens of the state to call the holiday by a
particular name.''
   ``It's not the holiday itself that's bothering me. It's the
name,'' said Hiromi Mineo Lima, 44, a Rhode Island resident for 16
years. ``I feel a bit of discrimination against the Japanese race.''
   Rhode Island veterans' groups are adamant that the name should
remain unchanged.
   ``Leave that ... holiday alone,'' said Lionel Poissant, state
service officer for the Rhode Island Veterans of Foreign Wars.
``It's too bad they didn't think of that when they attacked us.''
   Japan surrendered on Aug. 15, 1945. Germany's surrender, the old
``V-E Day'' for ``Victory in Europe,'' came May 7, 1945.
   Attorney Wood said the holiday's nickname ``discriminates on the
basis of race against Japanese-Americans'' and ``impugns the
character of Japanese-Americans in the United States, many of whose
families have been here for generations, or many of whom fought in
World War II.''
   Mindful of the popularity of the long weekend, politicians have
never seriously discussed repealing the holiday, established in
1948.
   There have been attempts in the General Assembly to change its
name to ``Peace Day'' or ``Remembrance Day,'' but all have been
sunk by the powerful veterans' lobby.
   The legislature did pass a resolution in 1987 reaffirming the
``Victory Day'' name after concerns were raised that the holiday
would make it more difficult for Rhode Island to attract Japanese
business.
   ``They started the war. We won the war,'' said Rene Bobola,
president of the Central Falls Veterans Council. ``We insulted
them? They insulted us by attacking.''
</TEXT>
