<FIRST>u w AM-Leland-Reax 1stLd-writethru a0690 08-13 1143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-Reax, 1st Ld-writethru, a0690,1180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Messages of Sorrow Pour In From Across The Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS word in lead graf to Ethiopia, updates with Mitchell
comment by adding new graf after 9th graf previous, `House Minority'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Sunday that Rep. Mickey
Leland was ``engaged in a noble cause _ trying to feed the hungry''
when his plane crashed on its way to a refugee camp in Ethiopia.
   The president, who ordered U.S. military aircraft into the
search for Leland last week, was among the first to express
condolences when an Air Force helicopter carrying one of Leland's
friends and congressional colleagues found the charred wreckage in
a mountain ravine.
   Bush, at Camp David, Md., for the weekend was notified by
telephone by his national security adviser soon after the downed
plane was found.
   Flags were quickly lowered to half staff at the White House and
elsewhere in official Washington and national leaders expressed
sorrow at the loss of the Texas Democratic congressman and other
members of the traveling party.
   Leland, chairman of the House Select Committee on Hunger,
vanished Monday after taking off from Addis Ababa for a refugee
camp on the Sudanese border. It was his second trip to the Horn of
Africa since March to promote relief efforts for hundreds of
thousands of Sudanese who face starvation.
   ``I have known, admired and worked with Mickey Leland for many
years,'' Bush said. ``His sense of compassion and desire to help
those in need has aided millions of people from Houston to Addis
Ababa.''
   House Speaker Tom Foley said the House had lost one of its most
dedicated, committed and energetic members.
   Foley has authorized Majority Whip William H. Gray III, D-Pa.,
and Rep. Ronald V. Dellums, D-Calif, chairman of the Congressional
Black Caucus, to travel to Addis Ababa and accompany the bodies of
Leland and U.S. staff back to the United States.
   House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel has designated Reps. Bill
Emerson, ranking Republican on the hunger committee, and Jack
Fields, R-Texas, to accompany the group.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, called Leland
``a respected public servant who was dedicated to the people of
Texas and to all Americans.''
   Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., is already in Ethiopia and was on
the helicopter that found the wreckage. Rep. Alan Wheat, D-Mo.,
also went to the African country earlier to aid the search.
   ``In his search to look at into the plight of the world's most
desperate and hungry individuals, Rep. Leland represented the best
in compassion that we as a nation possess,'' Foley said. ``His was
a mission which, as we all know all too well now, was fraught with
potential danger.''
   Gray said Leland's loss ``is the world's loss'' and ``deprives
us all of a man whose compassion, commitment and leadership in the
war against hunger saved the lives of tens of thousands of the
world's children. Those of us who are his colleagues and friends
can best keep his spirit alive by renewing our commitment to the
cause for which he gave his life: eradicating hunger both here and
around the world.'
   Leland's wife, six-weeks pregnant with their second child,
remained in seclusion at her home in Houston.
   Members of the congressman's Washington staff, which had
conducted numerous press briefings during the search, received
congressional colleagues and friends privately in Leland's Rayburn
House Office Building suite of offices on Sunday.
   Among those visiting was the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who had prayed
with Leland's staff and friends during the weeklong vigil. He told
reporters the Houston Democrat had worked tirelessly to ``prick the
conscience of Congress'' about the starving in Africa.
   ``I have watched him stand in these halls and literally break
down crying, trying to appeal to other congresspeople to be
sensitive to the fact that people in Ethiopia ... were clutching to
his ankles and dying before his eyes, with worms and flies
devouring their bodies.
   ``And with that sense of passion and moral imperative he kept
going back again and again and again,'' Jackson said.
   Dellums said the those aboard the aircraft _ including a staff
member, Joyce Francine Williams _ ``gave their lives nobly, in an
effort to advocate on behalf of people much less fortunate than
themselves.
   ``And I believe that the nation and the world have lost a
considerable number of very caring and compassionate and concerned
human beings,'' said Dellums.
   Describing him as someone ``who wore his feelings and compassion
right out in the open, in a very vulnerable and caring and
wonderful way,'' Dellums said he would miss Leland ``beyond
comprehension.''
   Other House and Senate members, the State Department and civil
rights leaders were among those expressing their grief.
   ``There is a special Jewish word that describes Mickey Leland,
`mensch' _ it means `a real human being.' The Anti-Defamation
League has been privileged to know and work with him,'' said league
national director Abraham H. Foxman.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said Leland died as he lived: ``On
a mission of mercy and hope for victims of poverty, injustice,
racism and hunger. Where ever suffering people existed on our
planet, Mickey Leland wanted to be there to help.''
   The State Department called Leland an outstanding statesman and
humanitarian and praised his relentless efforts on behalf of the
hungry.
   Mark L. Edelman, administrator of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, which had four employees aboard the
plane, said the traveling party represented the best in America's
tradition of reaching out to those in need.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas said: ``Mickey Leland was a strong
representative, a champion of the helpless and he was my good
friend. Mrs. Bentsen and I jin his family and many friends around
the world in mourning his death.''
   Texas' other senator, Republican Phil Gramm, said his heart went
out to Leland's family ``in this tragic time. He will be missed.''
   Hosea Williams, a veteran civil rights leader and Atlanta city
councilman, called Leland ``truly a human rights warrior.''
   ``I don't know that I've met a congressman in Washington that
was more sensitive or committed,'' Williams said. ``Not only Texas
but the country has lost one of its most relevant black leaders.''
   The Rev. Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, said Leland brought ``a real sense of
urgency on poverty'' to his work in Congress.
   ``Mickey was sensitive to the issue of hunger and it bothered
him deeply that in Africa, the homeland, hunger was ravaging the
population,'' Lowery said.
   In Houston, friends and colleagues streamed into Leland's
downtown office as news spread that the wreckage had been
discovered.
   Rep. Mike Andrews, a Houston Democrat, said with a breaking
voice, ``This is a very difficult time for Houston. We have lost
one of our most important leaders, and I've lost a very good
friend.''
</TEXT>
