<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strikes     08-13 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strikes,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nationalist Strikes Threatened in Three Republics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities, dealing with a strike in
Estonia, face new work stoppages in the republics of Azerbaijan and
Georgia over nationalist issues, union leaders said Sunday.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda said Sunday that as many as
40,000 Russian-speaking workers in Estonia were striking to protest
what they feel are discriminatory laws recently passed on
preserving the Estonian language and limiting the voting rights of
immigrants. Pravda sided with their demands.
   The People's Front of Azerbaijan called a general strike Monday
in ``non-strategic industries'' to demand local Communist Party
officials move to a more democratic structure, said activist Aidin
Amirbekov in a telephone interview.
   In Georgia, pro-independence activists had called for a general
strike to begin Tuesday. There were conflicting reports on whether
it would proceed.
   The ethnic Russian strikers in Estonia won support from a key
source Sunday. Under the headline, ``And what about civil rights?''
Pravda charged that the new Estonian election law, which sets tough
residency requirements, violates the Soviet constitutional equal
rights provision.
   ``As is known, the Constitution has not yet been abandoned,''
Pravda said.
   The article criticized the Estonian lawmakers, who have led the
call for human rights guarantees, for restricting the voting rights
of non-Estonians.
   The new law limits voting to residents who have lived in the
same district for two years or anywhere in Estonia for five years.
Candidates must live in the same place for five years, or in
Estonia for 10 years.
   A new language law requires most workers to learn Estonian. Many
Russian workers have not, even after decades of living in Estonia,
and natives complain that many police and ambulance personnel
cannot understand their language.
   A Moscow activist said workers in the Azerbaijan capital of Baku
demonstrated for a second night Sunday, but Amirbekov, speaking
from the town, denied that report.
   Amirbekov said workers at manufacturing plants are being asked
to strike Monday to support demands that local leaders ``find
political solutions instead of military ones'' to the republic's
ethnic violence, which has caused dozens of deaths. He said workers
in strategic industries, such as Baku's extensive oil complex, were
asked to stay on the job.
   Some activists in Baku are demanding removal of Soviet troops
from the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh and an end to
curfews in the republic, but Amirbekov said authorities believe
relations are too tense to consider that step.
   Azerbaijan, which traditionally is Shiite Moslem, has been
embroiled in a dispute with neighboring Armenia, whose population
is mainly Christian, over control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region.
Nagorno-Karabakh is part of Azerbaijan, but its population is
predominantly Armenian, and Armenia wants to annex it.
   In Estonia, work has at least partially halted at 26 enterprises
in the capital of Tallinn and at 13 factories in Kohtla-Jarve, the
labor newspaper Trud said Sunday. Train workers were on strike and
the state airline Aeroflot carried only emergency supplies and
passengers, Trud said.
   The Russians, most of who work in heavy industrial plants, also
object to a new national decision to give Estonia and the two other
Baltic republics, free rein over its economy. In asserting their
rights, ethnic Estonians have angered immigrant workers from Russia
and elsewhere.
   The workers are demanding that factories with a mainly
Russian-speaking labor force remain the property of the national
government rather than be handed over to Estonia.
   Artur Kapityem at the Russians' strike headquarters in Tallinn
said by telephone that leaders were in Moscow to meet with Kremlin
leaders since they have refused to negotiate with Estonian
officials.
   ``We no longer trust the republic's leadership,'' Tass quoted M.
Lysenko of the strike committee as saying.
   Kapityem denied Pravda's report that criminal charges had been
filed against labor leaders under an emergency Estonian decree
banning the strike.
   Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the
population. Russians make up about a third of the 1.6 million
people.
</TEXT>
