<FIRST>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 4thLd-Writethru a0668 08-13 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0668,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Columbia Finishes Secret Military Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs, 8-9, `The landing ...,' with 6 grafs to UPDATE with
crew arrival in Houston, edit to conform; picks up 10th graf, `The shuttle's
...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos EAB1,3,5, LaserColor EAB1c</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oldest space shuttle
glided to a perfect landing in the Mojave Desert on Sunday,
completing a secret mission to deploy a spy satellite and
reportedly conduct ``Star Wars'' experiments.
   ``A super team and a great machine _ welcome home, Columbia,''
Frank Culbertson, an astronaut from Mission Control in Houston,
said as the five-man crew landed shortly after sunrise, ending a
five-day, one hour and 56-minute journey of more than 2 million
miles.
   Columbia, though dirty, sustained little damage to the tiles
that protect it from the heat of the fiery re-entry, and no tiles
appeared to be missing, said Ed Jenner, shuttle support manager for
the Air Force at Edwards.
   It was the first mission in 3{ years for Columbia, which
inaugurated shuttle flights in 1981. Columbia's last flight ended
10 days before the January 1986 Challenger disaster that killed its
crew of seven.
   ``It was an apparently perfect landing,'' observed Nancy Lovato,
a spokeswoman for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   ``Welcome home, space cowboy!'' friends and relatives yelled at
pilot Richard Richards shortly before he and the other astronauts
departed aboard two Gulfstream jets bound for Johnson Space Center
in Houston.
   Richards told a crowd of about 100 spectators that Columbia's
mission represented ``a reaffirmation that human beings belong in
space. We can do wonderful things there. We can excite our kids and
make our planet a better place to live.''
   The astronauts and their wives arrived in Houston around 4 p.m.
CDT. They were greeted by their families and about 300 cheering
friends and co-workers.
   ``It was a real privilege to participate in the restoration of
Columbia to flight status,'' the shuttle's commander, Air Force
Col. Brewster Shaw, told the crowd at Ellington Field. ``It was a
privilege to accomplish what we accomplished on this flight for the
United States of America.''
   ``It wasn't nice; it was fantastic,'' added Richards, a Navy
commander and one of three space rookies on the flight.
   After a 15-minute ceremony, the astronauts shook hands and
hugged many of the well-wishers before climbing into vans and
heading home with their families.
   The landing ended the 30th mission of the shuttle program.
Columbia, for a years a ``hangar queen'' that was stripped of parts
to keep other shuttles flying, had undergone more than 250
modifications called for after the Challenger disaster.
   The other crew members were Navy Cmdr. David Leestma, Army Lt.
Col. James Adamson and Air Force Col. Mark Brown.
   The shuttle's sonic booms startled slumbering Los Angeles as it
hurtled across California. Minutes later, Shaw guided the 97-ton
orbiter to a 6:37 a.m. PDT landing on a hard clay runway, the
aircraft trailing a plume of dust.
   A news blackout was imposed on the mission by the Air Force. But
Air Force Secretary Donald Rice said Wednesday that a satellite was
deployed by the astronauts during their first day in orbit on
Tuesday.
   Rice maintained the official silence about the satellite's
purpose, but it is widely believed to be a 10-ton spy satellite
designed to take detailed photographs of military targets over a
wide area of the globe, including most of the Soviet Union. It
would help the United States verify Soviet compliance with arms
agreements.
   The shuttle crew also reportedly monitored military sites on
Earth and was believed to have conducted experiments related to the
``Star Wars'' missile defense program.
   The shuttle landed in perfect weather, with unrestricted
visibility. The few people gathered to watch on Rogers Dry Lake
also were treated to a view of the Perseid meteor shower, which
sprinkled the sky with shooting stars.
   The Air Force base 80 miles north of Los Angeles has been host
to as many as half a million people for shuttle landings but was
closed to the public Sunday because of the Pentagon's demand for
secrecy.
   The news media were allowed to watch and record the landing from
about two miles.
   The Department of Defense said secrecy was needed to ``limit an
adversary's ability to determine the mission of a given DOD shuttle
flight.''
</TEXT>
