<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Fundamentalist     08-13 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Fundamentalist,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fundamentalist Leader Released, Says He Is Under House Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fundamentalist Moslem preacher charged
with anti-government activities has been released from jail, but he
said Sunday he was under virtual house arrest.
   Omar Abdel-Rahman, who is blind, was acquitted twice of charges
connected to the assassination of President Anwar Sadat in October
1981. He and 48 other defendants now are being tried on charges of
illegal possession of weapons, attempting to kill a police officer
and assault.
   The charges are punishable by death.
   On Thursday, a state security court trying the 49 ordered the
release of 25 prisoners, including Abdel-Rahman. It ordered one
defendant, who is charged with bombing a theater in the southern
town of Fayoum, to remain in detention. The 23 others accused in
the case had not been jailed.
   Abdel-Rahman, contacted by telephone at his home in Fayoum,
said, ``I'm in good health.'' He has high blood pressure and
diabetes.
   ``There are security forces around my house,'' he said. ``They
have stopped me from going out to pray at the mosque. They are not
letting me out at all and are arresting my visitors.''
   Maj. Gen. Wagih Issa of the Interior Ministry denied
Abdel-Rahman's claims and said, ``He is free to move. Whoever wants
to visit him may do so freely.''
   The ministry, which is in charge of internal security,
reportedly had invoked emergency regulations to extend the
detention of the 25 who were released under the court order.
   Abdel-Rahman returned to his home Friday night.
   The emergency law has been in force since Sadat's assassination.
It gives police broad powers of search and arrest without charge
and bans unauthorized demonstrations and strikes.
   Abdel-Rahman, a former theology professor at Assiut University
south of Fayoum, heads a fundamentalist Moslem group that demands
the immediate and full full implementation of the Islamic law, or
Sharia.
   The government claims 90 percent of the existing law conforms to
Sharia.
   Abdel-Rahman was accused of inspiring the gunmen who killed
Sadat and was acquitted. He also was found innocent in a later
trial of 300 Moslem fundamentalists charged with an attempted coup
after Sadat's assassination.
   In both cases, the prosecution said Abdel-Rahman was the
spiritual leader of an underground group called Jihad that was
dedicated to the overthrow of the government. He was released in
1985 following the second acquittal.
   The current charges against him and 48 others involve an
anti-government demonstration on April 7 that the prosecution
claims Abdel-Rahman led.
   Police rounded up about 2,500 Moslem fundamentalists for
questioning after the demonstration.
</TEXT>
