<SECOND>AM-PLO,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman Says PLO Agrees To Elections If They End Israeli Occupation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the Palestine Liberation
Organization said Sunday the PLO is ready for elections in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip if it is guaranteed the balloting will end
Israeli occupation of the territories.
   ``I hereby announce that the PLO is ready for elections tomorrow
if it is guaranteed freedom and democracy,'' said Bassam Abu
Sharif, a spokesman for PLO chairman Yasser Arafat, told the
British Broadcasting Corp.
   ``We are ready if the world community will guarantee that the
elections we go to will be one step in a process that will lead to
an end of the Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza,'' he
said in the interview in Tunisia, where Fatah, the main group in
the PLO, held its congress last week.
   The congress called for intensified military action to end the
Israeli occupation of the territories and rejected Israeli Premier
Yitzhak Shamir's plan for elections.
   ``What we are after is freedom, like any other people,'' Sharif
said. ``We are asking the Israelis to come and sit down and talk to
us.''
   But he said that as long as Israel occupies the territories the
PLO will continue to lead the uprising in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. More than 530 Palestinians and 38 Israelis have been killed
in the uprising that began in December 1987.
   Shamir has proposed elections in the occupied lands and talks
with the elected Palestinian representatives on an interim
self-rule solution for the 1.7 million Arabs in the territories.
   In Jerusalem, an Israeli government official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said he saw nothing new in Abu Sharif's
statement.
   He said the PLO's repeated demand for guaranteeing creation of a
Palestinian state before any negotiations amounts to rejection of
Israel's call for talks without conditions.
