<FIRST>r a AM-RiteAid     08-13 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rite Aid,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rite Aid Stockholder OK'd Pharmacy Panel Selection, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior aide to U.S. Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh owned Rite Aid Corp. stock when he participated in the
1986 appointment of an executive of the drugstore chain to the
state pharmacy board, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported Sunday.
   The aide, Murray G. Dickman, also was a guest of Rite Aid
chairman Alex Grass and his two sons, both company executives, on a
January 1983 trip by corporate jet from Harrisburg to New Orleans
to watch Penn State play in the Sugar Bowl, according to the
newspaper.
   At the time, Dickman was secretary of administration under
then-Gov. Thornburgh. Dickman is now assistant to the attorney
general.
   Rite Aid, the nation's largest retail pharmacy chain, and its
president, Martin L. Grass, have been indicted in Cleveland on
state bribery charges.
   Grass, who is accused of delivering a $33,000 bribe and other
benefits to a member of the Ohio Board of Pharmacy, is to be
arraigned Tuesday.
   Dickman said he was infuriated by implications in the Inquirer's
story about his time in state government.
   ``I did nothing improper according to the laws,'' Dickman said
in an interview Saturday night with The Associated Press. ``I am
truly offended.''
   Dickman owned 400 of 40 million shares in Rite Aid, U.S. Justice
Department spokesman David Runkel said. Based on the stock's 1986
price range on the New York Stock Exchange, his interest was worth
between $9,700 and $14,200.
   ``That's not a very big stake in the company,'' Runkel said.
Runkel, who also served in Thornburgh's gubernatorial
administration, added that under Pennsylvania law, Dickman did
nothing improper.
   As secretary of administration, Dickman was the key aide on
appointments to state boards. He approved a recommendation that
Thornburgh name Rite Aid executive Frederick H. Wendte to a seat on
the Board of Pharmacy, the Inquirer said. The governor went along
with the recommendation on June 4, 1986.
   Dickman said Saturday that he was aware of the appointment, but
to insinuate that he had an effect on the decision was
``preposterous.''
   He said he sold the stock in 1986, most likely toward the end of
the year.
   Dickman left Thornburgh's cabinet on Nov. 15, 1986 to accept a
$100,000-a-year job as a senior vice president of the
Harrisburg-based company. Thornburgh's second term as governor
ended in January 1987.
   Thornburgh accepted a seat on the Rite Aid board of directors in
April 1987 and served until he became attorney general in August
1988. Dickman left his Rite Aid job in November 1987 and joined
Thornburgh in the Justice Department last August.
   He was not required to list the Rite Aid stock on disclosures
filed publicly with the state Ethics Commission and did not do so.
He disclosed it within Thornburgh's administration on the more
detailed reports required by the governor code of conduct.
   Dickman called the 1983 Sugar Bowl trip ``a social call'' from
his friend Roger Grass, then a Rite Aid vice president.
   The trip was not disclosed although Thornburgh's code of conduct
barred officials from accepting gifts or entertainment.
   Dickman said he cleared the trip with the governor's Office of
General Counsel.
   ``It doesn't appear that the legal advice was sound,'' Runkel
quoted Thornburgh as having said Friday.
</TEXT>
