<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-13 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Dies of Gunshot Wound, Gaza Strip Workers Attacked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old Palestinian died Sunday of wounds
suffered in a clash with soldiers, and troops dispersed bands of
masked youths attacking Gaza Strip workers applying for entry
permits to Israel.
   Arab hospital officials said 11 Palestinians were shot and
wounded Sunday in clashes with Israeli soldiers in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The death raised to 536 the number of Arabs killed in the
20-month-old Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories.
Thirty-eight Israelis have been slain in the violence.
   Also Sunday, one of Israel's leading religious figures said that
under Jewish law, the concept of preserving Jewish lives took
precedence over all other commandments, including settling the
biblical land of Israel.
   But Rabbi Ovadia Yosef of the ultraorthodox Shas political party
did not make the anticipated religious ruling on returning
territories to preserve Jewish lives.
   He said relinquishing territories at this time is not realistic
because there is no Arab partner for peace.
   Jewish settlers living in the occupied West Bank claim there is
a religious imperative for them to settle there.
   Yosef, addressing an assembly of about 1,000 ultraorthodox Jews
in Jerusalem, did not retract his statement made to Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak last month that Israel could return
territories to avoid loss of lives in a war.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, speaking at the same assembly,
said he favored territorial compromise so Israel could maintain a
Jewish majority in its own state.
   ``Between claiming our right to the (biblical) land of Israel _
and I don't doubt that right _ and losing the Jewishness of the
state ... I want a Jewish state within its own borders with the
Jewish traditions,'' he said.
   Rabin's left-leaning Labor party favors territorial compromise
while Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc is
opposed.
   The latest Palestinian to die in the uprising was Fayez Jaber
Abu Obeid, 16. The army said he was shot during a clash with troops
Saturday at the Rafah refugee camp in the Gaza Strip, and he died
at Tel Hashomer Hospital.
   Also in the Gaza Strip, a 32-year-old taxi driver, Mustafa
Darwish Abu Dahrouj, was fatally shot Saturday, and Palestinian
sources said he was killed because it was believed he collaborated
with with Israeli authorities.
   He was the 95th Palestinian killed by fellow Arabs as a
suspected collaborator.
   Israeli soldiers fired tear gas and rubber bullets at youths
throwing stones at about 5,000 Palestinian workers applying for
entry permits near the Erez crossing in the Gaza Strip, Arab
witnesses said.
   An army spokesman said troopers dispersed rioters but no one was
injured seriously. He would not say if tear gas and rubber bullets
were used.
   Israel, in an effort to limit the uprising, is requiring all
Palestinians with jobs in Israel to have entry permits.
   Both Israel and leaders of the uprising are trying to control
the workers' movements.
   A military official said the fighting at Erez began after
officials turned away hundreds of people from an application office
because of the large number of workers waiting. The office has been
handling up to 1,000 applicants daily.
   About 50,000 Gazans work in Israel and for many families their
jobs are the only income. The military official said about 40,000
permits have been issued.
