<SECOND>AM-Fire Arrests,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Volunteer Firefighters Charged With Setting Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five volunteer firefighters and a
sixth person have been arrested and charged with setting 16 fires,
a newspaper reported Sunday.
   The arrests Friday grew out of an investigation by police and
the arson squad of the Bergen County Prosecutor's Office into 50
suspicious fires, according to The Record of Hackensack.
   The 16 fires occurred in a railroad boxcar, trash bins, brush
and abandoned mattresses between January 1988 and last June. No one
was injured.
   The prosecutor's office said the fires ``were started by the
five borough firemen and one juvenile female who enjoyed watching
her boyfriend fight the arson blaze.'' There was no other
indication of motive.
   The six were charged in East Rutherford Municipal Court with
failure to report or control dangerous fires, the Record reported.
All but the juvenile, whose name police did not release, were
charged with criminal mischief. Four of the people charged were
released on their own recognizance.
   Kurt Dechert, 21, and Randall Gillies, 20, were also charged
with arson. Dechert was released on $50,000 bail. Gillies was
released on $20,000 bail, the Record said.
   Also charged were Dechert's brother, Peter, 18, James Rivelli,
19, and Sean Reilly, 20.
   The five volunteer firefighters were to be suspended from the
East Rutherford department until the outcome of their cases, Fire
Chief Alfred Klamerus told the Record.
