<FILEID>AP-NR-08-13-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Berlin-Trooper     08-13 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Berlin-Trooper,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Border Guard Says Majority of Troopers Ignored Orders To Shoot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto BER8</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Berlin Wall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than a year platoon leader Falk Turba
patrolled the border between East and West Germany, his automatic
rifle at the ready to stop anyone attempting to flee to the West.
   In July, he slipped away from his comrades, tossed his rifle
aside and scrambled over the barbed-wire and concrete barriers to
West Germany.
   ``I just couldn't take it anymore,'' Turba said in an interview
in West Berlin on Sunday, the 28th anniversary of the building of
the Berlin Wall.
   Turba, 20, spoke of the daily life of communist East Germany's
elite border troopers _ young men selected by Communist Party and
military officials because of their loyality to the state.
   Turba, who grew up in Dresden, said border guards were told in
April that a shoot-to-kill order against civilians trying to flee
East Germany had been lifted.
   But he said most of his comrades had quietly ignored the order
during their border service.
   ``Only about 10 percent of the hard-core, gung-ho troops would
shoot at an unarmed civilian attempting to flee,'' Turba said.
``They're the macho types who like strutting around with their
machine guns looking tough.''
   But he said it was a great risk for the border guards to allow
someone to escape.
   ``If you let someone escape, you go to prison,'' he said. ``It's
also very risky because you patrol in pairs, and you never know
what the other guy is thinking or what he would do.
   ``But I hoped, and many others did as well, that I would never
have to arrest someone.''
   He said electronic listening devices and alarm systems, attack
dogs and rows of barbed-wire usually slowed would-be escapees long
enough that border troops could arrest them.
   Many of those caught were given long prison terms.
   According to West German statistics, 191 people have been killed
trying to escape since the Berlin Wall was erected in 1961 and the
border between the two Germanies was sealed by barriers.
   But about 218,000 people managed to escape including 2,614
border troops, according to the statistics.
   Turba said he decided to flee because he had little hope of
political and economic changes in his country.
   Unlike Hungary and Poland, where reform communists have
succeeded in expanding freedoms, East German leader Erich Honecker
maintains a hard-line policy.
   Turba said a growing number of border guards are openly
questioning the nation's border policy, which East German officials
contend is necessary ``to protect socialism from Western
plunderers.''
   ``You sit in your freezing bunker or guard tower and begin to
ask yourself what this border is for and what you are doing,''
Turba said. ``You reach a point where you realize its senseless and
brutal.''
   He said morale among border units is slumping because the
increasing number of escape attempts brings additional pressure
from their officers.
   Frustration and disillusionment lead many troopers to break
regulations, according to Turba.
   ``Some people bring books to read in the towers. Others rig
their field radios to tune into Western broadcasts. The political
officer once took off to go hunting,'' he said.
   On July 12, Turba told his comrades he had problems with his
motorcycle and he needed to take it for a test drive. He roared
over a hill, coasted to the border barriers and bounded to freedom.
   ``There are a lot of weak points along the border and we know
them best,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890813-0077 </DOCNO>
