<FIRST>u w AM-WhiteHouse-Leland 1stLd-Writethru a0702 08-13 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House-Leland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Expresses Sadness at Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs graf 13, ``White House, to CORRECT that departure date
for plane to return bodies not yet set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush expressed his ``profound
sadness'' Sunday at the crash in Ethiopia of an airplane that was
carrying Rep. Mickey Leland and 15 other persons.
   Returning to the White House by helicopter from Camp David, Bush
also conveyed his thanks to the government of Ethiopia and the U.S.
military team that found the wreckage.
   ``I want to ... simply express the profound sadness that we feel
at the loss of the lives in Ethiopia,'' said the president.
   He said he had not yet spoken with the Texas congressman's wife,
Alison, ``but I certainly express my profound sadness, profound
regrets over all of this to her, and to their child.''
   His somber mood lifting for a moment, Bush recalled with a smile
that ``in a happier time,'' both Lelands had been his guests at a
recent barbecue for members of Congress on the South Lawn of the
White House.
   ``It's a sadness for everybody. He was an outstanding man, a man
of great humor,'' Bush said of the Democratic congressman from his
hometown of Houston.
   ``Everyone from Texas knew of his lively nature and his
commitment to helping others. So it is with profound sadness that I
convey to his family and to his colleagues and to his staff the
regrets that all Americans feel,'' the president said.
   Bush also thanked ``everybody that involved themselves in this
almost unprecedented search, and certainly the government of
Ethiopia, who could not, I'm told, have been more cooperative.''
   Asked if the Ethiopians had requested assistance to determine
how the crash occurred, Bush replied: ``Not that I know of, but
they certainly will get any cooperation on that from us, just as we
did, have fully cooperated on the search.
   He added, ``It has been unprecedented and the result is terrible
but I must commend the courageous men and women in the armed
services that joined in this search. It was really a very difficult
search, and they did it well, against bad weather, a lot of things.
So it was quite special and showed us pulling together.''
   When a reporter asked if Bush had anything to say about the
cause Leland died for _ fighting world hunger _ the president said
no.
   ``This isn't a time to say anything but how sad and profoundly
sad I feel about the fate of the people on that plane,'' said Bush.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Frederick C.
McClure, Bush's chief liaison to Congress, and a deputy, Nicholas
Calio, would join a congressional delegation that will fly to Addis
Ababa on an official mission to bring back the bodies after they
are identified. It was uncertain when they will depart.
   Earlier, the White House issued a statement from Bush in which
the president said he was ``truly saddened to hear that the
discovery of Mickey Leland's aircraft revealed that apparently
there were no survivors of this tragic accident.''
   ``Mickey Leland and the other members of his traveling party,
both Americans and Ethiopians, were engaged in a noble cause _
trying to feed the hungry. I have known, admired and worked with
Mickey Leland for many years. His sense of compassion and desire to
help those in need has aided millions of people from Houston to
Addis Ababa,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
