<FIRST>u i AM-SovietExpelled     08-13 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Expelled,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Expelled Soviet Diplomat Interested in Radar System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet diplomat expelled two weeks
ago had tried to obtain information about the advanced radar system
on Sweden's new warplane JAS 39 Gripen, a newspaper said Sunday.
   The Stockholm daily Svenska Dagbladet did not identify the
official but said he was posted at the Soviet consulate general in
Goteborg.
   According to the paper, he tried for several years to obtain
information from employees of Ericsson Radar Electronics AB in
nearby Molndal.
   Foreign Ministry sources and news reports said Swedish security
interests did not suffer but would have been at risk had the Soviet
diplomat continued his activities.
   The diplomat was expelled two weeks ago, but the Foreign
Ministry did not announce the expulsion until Friday.
   A ministry spokesman Sunday refused comment on the newspaper
report.
   Last year, two Soviet citizens were expelled from Sweden.
   In October 1988, a Stockholm-based Soviet trade official was
asked to leave Sweden after being accused of industrial espionage.
   That April, a Soviet businessman living in Goteborg was expelled
after trying to obtain information about foreign and Swedish
technology.
