<FIRST>r a AM-ManacledSwimmer     08-13 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manacled Swimmer,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manacled Swimmer Fails in Attempt to Cross Lake Erie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN F. BONFATTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man tried to swim handcuffed across part
of Lake Erie on Sunday in a symbolic fund raiser for China's
beleaguered pro-democracy movement, but had to stop short of his
goal when a support boat sank.
   ``We weren't doing bad; we're just disappointed we didn't
finish,'' said Maynard ``Magilla'' Schaus, who with three Chinese
students was trying to swim 10 miles from Crystal Beach, Ontario,
to the Erie Basin Marina here. They were forced to stop about eight
miles into the 10-mile swim.
   Two swimmers from the Erie, Pa., area had better luck than the
38-year-old Buffalo actor and writer. Bob North, 35, and Harvey
Snell, 38, came ashore in North East, Pa., on Sunday morning after
a 26- to 30-mile swim that began the previous evening at Long
Point, Canada.
   It was the first time anyone had completed a swim across the
lake since 1975.
   The outboard boat that sank during Schaus' shorter swim was one
of two support boats, and carried a styrofoam replica of the
``Goddess of Democracy'' statue that Chinese students erected in
Beijing's Tienanmen Square before the June military crackdown.
   The boat began taking on water about two miles from Buffalo and
sank within two minutes, Schaus said. The swimmers had been in the
water for about seven hours when it was called off at 3:30 p.m.
   A passing boater and the Erie County sheriff's marine patrol
helped the swimmers and the people in the boat that sank, Schaus
said. He said the marine patrol gave him a ticket for having an
unregistered rowboat _ the boat that didn't sink.
   Schaus said he didn't know why the other boat sank, but
speculated that a large wave or a loose drainage plug may have been
the cause.
   Schaus has made the swim twice before for other charities, but
Sunday was the first time he did it handcuffed, which he said was a
metaphor for the loss of freedom in China. To swim, he used a
modified dog paddle.
   Xianglong Zhang, one of the students at the State University of
New York at Buffalo who swam with Schaus, said he was more
disappointed for Schaus than in his own failure to finish the swim.
   ``Without this accident, he would have been successful in
reaching here,'' said Zhang.
   Schaus said he made the effort ``to demonstrate that there are
Americans who care about standing up for freedom, people who
believe in the tenets this country was founded on.''
   The swim was sponsored by the Chinese Students Club at the
university to help victims of the crackdown on the pro-democracy
movement and provide information on the movement.
   The sponsors were unable to say how much money was pledged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
