<FIRST>r a AM-BoxOffice     08-13 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Box Office,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Abyss' Makes Splash at Weekend Box Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new release ``The Abyss'' appeared to make
a splash at the weekend box office with an estimated $8.6 million
in receipts, putting the film second only to ``Parenthood''
nationwide, an industry source said Sunday.
   The Ron Howard-directed ``Parenthood'' was expected to take in
$9.6 million, and the third-place spot was expected to go to ``A
Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child,'' bringing in some $8.3
million, said the source, who asked not to be identified.
   Complete figures were due Monday.
   ``The Abyss,'' the $43 million underwater adventure by 20th
Century Fox, made a solid opening Wednesday, taking in $2.1 million
at the national box office, Daily Variety reported.
   ``The Abyss'' stars Ed Harris as the foreman of an experimental
underwater oil rig commandeered by a group of Navy SEALS to salvage
a U.S. nuclear submarine. Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio plays the
foreman's estranged wife.
   The film was shot in large part in an unfinished South Carolina
nuclear power plant's cooling tank, filled with 7.5 million gallons
of heated and filtered water.
   The movie underwent 3{ months of principal filming, 40 percent
of it underwater. Its filming required director James Cameron,
actors, camera operators and a squad of technicians to remain
underwater for up to 10 hours a day.
</TEXT>
