<SECOND>AM-Leland-Memorial,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leland's High School, College Classmates Gather For Memorial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Leland-Reax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meeting that had been planned as a celebration
of hope became a memorial service Sunday when Rep. Mickey Leland's
high school and college classmates heard that the congressman's
plane had crashed in Ethiopia.
   ``Sometimes, they fall for a purpose,'' Howard Johnson of the
Houston Independent School District told about 400 people gathered
in the Phillis Wheatley High School auditorium.
   Many in the audience were classmates of Leland from his days at
Phillis Wheatley and Texas Southern University.
   The airplane carrying Leland and 15 other people disappeared on
Monday en route to a refugee camp, and Sunday's service had been
planned as one of hope for the 44-year-old Texas Democrat's safety.
   But searchers found the wreckage of the plane scattered on a
rugged mountainside. All aboard were believed dead.
   Leland's trip to Ethiopia was typical of the man, said Phillis
Wheatley classmate Madeline Williams. ``He just set out to do
things and didn't care whether or not it endangered his life,'' she
said.
   Leland had been touring Ethiopia in his capacity as chairman of
the House Select Committee on Hunger, and Johnson urged his
audience to continue the congressman's quest to help the hungry.
   ``Mickey would love that,'' Johnson said.
  
</TEXT>
