<HEAD>Edinburgh Festival Feeling Better About Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students from Virginia waved from a
truck and Soviet Georgians danced down Princes Street in Sunday's
parade opening the 43rd Edinburgh International Festival.
   Crowds estimated by police at 150,000 watched the cavalcade.
   Leaders of big business have joined festival president Sir
Yehudi Menuhin, the violinist, to launch a $16 million trust fund
to support the festival.
   In the next three weeks, 1,150 shows will be given 9,500
performances by 8,600 participants _ 60 percent professional and 40
percent amateur _ at the official Edinburgh festival and the
unofficial Festival Fringe, which runs in tandem with it. The
festival ends Sept. 3.
   The Georgians, who danced behind a hammer-and-sickle flag at the
traditional parade, are among 87 dancers, musicians and singers
from the Soviet Union performing in and around Edinburgh.
   There are 35 U.S. groups presenting some 100 plays and shows,
with professional and college groups taking over church halls and
clubs.
   ``Is There Life After High School?'' is a song-and-sketch comedy
presented by the E.C. Glass High School of Lynchburg, Va., which
sent a group of 26 to the Fringe.
