<FIRST>r a AM-IdahoFires     08-13 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Idaho Fires,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lightning Adds To Woes, But Idaho Firefighters Holding Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters hustled to stamp out dozens of
small fires ignited by lightning Sunday, but held their own against
major forest and range fires that have scorched about 91,000 acres.
   Brief thunderstorms helped keep major fires from growing, but
the lightning that accompanied them sparked nearly 100 new
outbreaks in the Boise and Payette national forests alone,
officials said.
   Firefighters who parachuted into affected areas and firefighting
aircraft put out most of the new fires before they burned more than
an acre, said U.S. Forest Service fire information officer Carol
Tocco.
   In the Boise National Forest in central Idaho, firefighters
moved closer to containing a 45,524-acre fire and a 20,380-acre
blaze.
   The two fires were 90 percent contained by Sunday afternoon, and
officials projected full containment by Monday evening.
   Firefighters were having less success with two fires that have
scorched 13,300 acres in Payette National Forest.
   The fires had combined by Sunday to form one larger fire.
Efforts to contain it were augmented by two Army Blackhawk
helicopters that ferried firefighters to isolated edges of the
blaze.
   More than 6,500 firefighters and 1,400 military personnel have
battled 10 major fires in Idaho during recent weeks.
</TEXT>
