<FIRST>u i AM-Norway-Submarine     08-13 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Norway-Submarine,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norwegian Trawler Nets Unmarked Submarine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROMSOE, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian trawler caught an unmarked
submarine in its fishing net but the sub's crew used axes and
blowtorches to cut the vessel free and it fled without identifying
itself, a news report said Sunday.
   The trawler Orion was fishing Saturday near Bear Island, 250
miles off of northern Norway, when the submarine ran into its nets,
dragging the Orion backward, the ship's owner Jens-Petter Kraknes
told the Norwegian news agency NTB.
   It reported Kraknes said he decided not to release the submarine
unless it identified itself and the sub surfaced quickly. The
submarine crewemen refused to identify their craft and instead used
axes, blowtocrhes and sledgehammers to cut away the net, NTB said.
In about an hour the sub was freed and sailed away, Kraknes told
NTB.
   His report said the Orion fishermen saw no markings on the
vessel, which was in international waters, but they took
photographs of the vessel and they will be sent to Norway's
Northern Defense Command.
   Arild Isegg of the Norwegian Defense Ministry told NTB he was
``just about positive'' there were no submarines from the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization in the area, which is used by both
NATO and Soviet vessels.
</TEXT>
